ing Telangana High Court judgment that held that a person can be arrested by the competent authority in case of Goods and service tax evasion case.\nThe vacation bench of Chief Justice of India Ranjan Gogoi and Justice Aniruddha Bose, dismissing the Special Leave Petition, said that it is not inclined to interfere.','','','2019-06-29 07:05:57.786434','2019-06-29 07:10:22.306112',0,'Arrest_and_Gogai_Justice.jpg',1),(11,'new news','body goes here','','','2019-07-08 13:49:00.045011','2019-07-08 13:49:07.863651',1,'',1),(12,'FAQs on New GST Returns Forms','As per the press release issued by the Ministry of Finance dated 21-06-2019, the CBIC has proposed three new GST Returns forms, which shall be introduced in a phased manner - GST RET-1 (Monthly/Quarterly Normal), GST RET-2 (Sahaj), GST RET-3 (Sugam). The criterion on the basis of which these forms can be chosen by a supplier have been enumerated in the below article.','','','2019-07-17 13:55:48.396666','2019-07-17 13:59:33.488052',0,'faq.jpg',1),(13,'new news','body goes here','','','2019-07-17 14:02:16.886287','2019-07-19 14:14:16.953758',1,'',0),(14,'Shifting of transmission lines is not supply of goods, GST not applicable','GST : Where applicant (NHAI) is undertaking shifting of transmission towers/lines of RVPNL in course of diversification of Highways and it will bear overall cost of Highway diversification along with cost of shifting, dismantling and raising of transmission lines owned by RVPNL, since assets created by applicant, i.e., constructed power transmission lines being an immovable property, does not fall under definition of \'goods\' as mentioned in the GST Act, 2017, question of applicability of GST does not arise','','','2019-07-17 14:02:58.658635','2019-07-17 14:06:01.493660',0,'supply_of_goods.jpg',1),(15,'Automatic & traditional coffee maker not meant for domestic use classified under heading 8419, taxable @ 18% GST','Where applicant manufactured Automatic Electric Filter Coffee Maker and Manual, Electrically Warmed Filter Coffee Maker which are not meant for domestic use, it is held that products manufactured by applicant are classifiable under Heading No. 8419 and are taxable to CGST 9 per cent and SGST 9 per cent as per SI. No. 320 of Schedule III to Notification No. 01/2017-Central Tax (Rate) dated 28-6-2017 as amended by Notification No. 41/2017 dated 14-11-2017','','','2019-07-17 14:06:24.934552','2019-07-17 14:08:57.112036',0,'gst.jpg',1),(16,'Pumps manufactured & supplied to Indian Navy for commissioning its vessels & warships are taxed @ 5% GST','Forced lubrication pumps, emergency lube oil pumps, DG lub oil transfer pumps and triple screw pumps with spares and parts manufactured by applicant were parts of vessels classifiable under 8906 and themselves classifiable under chapter 8413, therefore, they were covered under entry at Sl. No. 252 of Schedule I of Notification No. 01/2017-C.T. (Rate) dated 28-6-2017 as amended at 25 per cent CGST and at Sl. No. 252 of Schedule I of Notification No. II(2)/CTR/532(d-4)/2017 vide G.O. (Ms) No. 62 dated 29-6-2017 as amended at 2.5 per cent SGST and at Sl. No. 252 of Schedule I of Notification No. 1/2017-Integrated Tax (Rate) dated 28-6-2017 as amended at 5 per cent IGST\n\n The applicant was engaged in manufacturing of triple screw pumps and parts thereof falling under chapter heading 8413 and supplying same to Indian Navy for intended use of same as \'parts of vessels & warships\' based on purchase order placed by them.\n\n The applicant preferred an application seeking advance ruling on question that whether triple screw pumps & parts thereof falling under chapter heading 8413 could be treated as parts of HSN 8901, 8902, 8904, 8905, 8906, 8907 attracting:\n\n IGST 5 per cent as per Schedule I (Sl. No. 252 of Notification No. 1/2017 - Integrated Tax (Rate) dated 28-6-2017 or not?\n\n CGST 2.5 per cent + SGST 2.5 per cent as per Schedule I (Sl. No. 252) of Notification No. 1/2017 - Central Tax (Rate) dated 28-6-2017 or not?\n\n Forced lubrication pumps, emergency lube oil pumps, DG lub oil transfer pumps and triple screw pumps manufactured by applicant supplied to India Navy for commissioning in its vessels and warships are parts of \'all types of vessels & warships\'.\n\n They are covered under entry at Sl. No. 252 of Schedule I of Notification No. 01/2017-C.T. (Rate) dated 28-6-2017 as amended at 2.5 per cent CGST and at Sl. No. 252 of Schedule I of Notification No. II (2)/CTR/532(d-4)/2017 vide G.O. (Ms) No. 62 dated 29-6-2017 as amended at 2.5 per cent SGST and at Sl. No. 252 of Schedule I of Notification No. 1/2017 - Integrated Tax (Rate) dated 28-6-2017 as amended at 5 per cent IGST.','','','2019-07-17 14:09:06.831105','2019-07-17 14:12:37.479401',0,'pupms.jpg',1),(17,'Impact of GST on Textile Industry: PIB','Ministry of Finance vide press release has stated that GST rates are lesser on garments and related articles as compared to the pre-GST regime. Also, the refund of accumulated ITC on fabrics has also been allowed to reduce the cost of fabrics. Govt. has taken various steps for promoting investments, exports in the textile sector.','','','2019-07-18 13:06:48.073950','2019-07-18 13:10:10.797970',0,'TEXTILE.jpg',1),(18,'Royalty/fees paid to obtain license for mining & exploration of natural resources taxable @18% GST','Licensing services for right to use minerals including its exploration and evaluation being provided by State of Rajasthan to applicant for which royalty is being paid is classifiable under 997337 and rate of GST on said service is 18 per cent\n\nFacts\n\n Applicant is engaged in business of crushing of Boulder resulting in to Broken or crushed Stone, Ballast in State of Rajasthan. It has been granted a mining lease for extracting \'Rough Boulder of Stone from mining\' by Rajasthan State Government on various terms and conditions as per Lease deed.\n\n State Mining Department of Rajasthan Government, collect royalty at time of dispatch of boulder from mining place. However, the State Mining Department of Rajasthan Government, has appointed a Contractor for collection of Royalty on behalf of Mining Department. The contractor collect royalty on boulder from recipient of boulder.\n\n Applicant is seeking Advance Ruling on classification of any goods or services or both.\n\nHeld\n\n For having assigned the rights to use the natural resources, the licensee companies are required to pay consideration in the form of annual license fee, lease charges, royalty, etc to the Government. The activity of assignment of rights to use natural resources is treated as supply of services and the licensee is required to pay tax on the amount of consideration paid in the form of royalty or any other form under reverse charge mechanism.\n\n The mining lease is governed by the Rajasthan Minor Minerals Concession Rules, 2017 (RMMCR). As per provisions of RMMCR, the applicant is required to pay dead rent or royalty (whichever is higher but not both). This activity of payment of dead rent or royalty is a supply of service (Licensing services for the right to use minerals including its exploration and evaluation) wherein the government of Rajasthan is supplier and the applicant is recipient. Thus, service provided by the State of Rajasthan to the applicant for which royalty is being paid is classifiable under 997337 and rate of GST on said service is 18 per cent (SGST 9 per cent +CGST 9 per cent).','','','2019-07-18 13:10:47.829795','2019-07-18 13:14:01.551698',0,'maining.jpg',1),(19,'Quartz Slabs are classified under heading 68101990, taxable @ 18% GST','Applicant a registered manufacturer-cum-supplier under GST is engaged in manufacture of Quartz Slabs (Artificial Stone). Slabs supplied by applicant are composed of 92 per cent quartz and 8 per cent resin binder. Thus, product can merit classification under residuary category of tariff entry 68101990 and applicable rate of GST on Quartz Slabs (Artificial Stone) is 18 per cent.','','','2019-07-18 13:15:53.677819','2019-07-18 13:17:08.079578',0,'gst_OZYRcGf.jpg',1),(20,'Co-operative Society not established/constituted by govt. is not liable to deduct TDS under GST','Where applicant is a co-operative society registered under Rajasthan Co-operative Societies Act, 1965 and deals in manufacturing of Milk and related milk products, but it is not established under Societies Registration Act, 1860 nor it is established/constituted by any Government (viz., Central Government/State Government/Local Authority), applicant does not fall under any category of section 51 of GST Act, 2017 and not liable to deduct tax at source (TDS) from payment made to vendors for providing/procuring taxable goods and services for making its supplies','','','2019-07-18 13:17:33.780156','2019-07-18 13:19:36.604317',0,'GST-Calculator-Software_1.png',1),(21,'CBIC issues clarification in respect of IT-enabled services provided by Indian suppliers to clients located abroad','On July 18, 2019, vide Circular No. 107/26/2019-GST, CBIC has cleared doubts relating to the supply of IT-enabled services such as call center, BPO & Intermediaries services provided by Indian suppliers to clients located abroad','','','2019-07-19 05:13:54.004167','2019-07-19 05:17:23.308855',0,'cbic.jpg',1),(22,'Goods sent/taken out of India for the purpose of exhibition or export promotion, not to be treated as export of goods','On July 18, 2019, vide Circular No. 108/27/2019-GST, CBIC has cleared doubts relating to goods sent/taken out of India for exhibition or on a consignment basis for export promotion, except when such activity satisfies the conditions laid in Schedule I of the CGST Act, cannot be considered as Zero-rated supply as per the provisions contained in section 16 of the IGST Act.','','','2019-07-19 05:19:12.813416','2019-07-19 05:20:30.962694',0,'export.jpg',1),(23,'ITC can be availed on import of iron ore to be used in furtherance of business if IGST is paid','Where applicant proposes to enter into a contract with a non-resident party for rendering service of conversion of iron ore into pellets and would be imported in India by applicant using its own GSTIN, though iron ore shall always remain property of non-resident, it is held that applicant is liable to pay IGST on import of iron ore. Applicant is eligible to avail input tax credit towards payment of IGST under section 16. Applicant is not eligible for refund of unutilized input tax credit on export of goods or services as per second proviso to sub-section 3 of section 54','','','2019-07-19 10:55:10.001216','2019-09-05 11:50:58.275163',1,'iron.jpg',1),(24,'ITC on Motor Vehicle purchased for providing trial runs to customers & capitalized in books is available','Where applicant purchases demo vehicles for promotion of sale by providing trial run to customer against tax invoices from supplier after paying taxes and capitalizes purchase of such vehicles in books of account, capital goods which are used in course or furtherance of business is entitle for Input Tax Credit, and thus, Input Tax Credit on Motor Vehicle purchased for demonstration purpose can be availed as Input Tax Credit on Capital Goods and set off against output tax payable under GST','','','2019-07-19 11:05:23.377158','2019-09-05 11:50:51.468231',0,'itc.jpg',0),(25,'Due date to make payment of taxes by Composition Dealers in form CMP-08 has been extended to July 31, 2019','On July 18, 2019, vide Notification No. 34/2019-Central Tax, CBIC has extended the due date for making payment of taxes in form GST CMP-08 by Composition dealers for the quarter April, 2019 to June, 2019 shall be July 31, 2019.','','','2019-07-19 11:07:43.984005','2019-09-05 11:50:49.914492',0,'GST-Composition-Scheme.png',1),(26,'Due date to make payment of taxes by Composition Dealers in form CMP-08 has been extended to July 31, 2019','On July 18, 2019, vide Notification No. 34/2019-Central Tax, CBIC has extended the due date for making payment of taxes in form GST CMP-08 by Composition dealers for the quarter April, 2019 to June, 2019 shall be July 31, 2019.','','','2019-07-19 11:10:30.143139','2019-07-19 11:13:06.395243',0,'exide_image.png',1),(27,'Refund application can now be filed for July 17-June 19 for IGST paid on export of services & supplies made to SEZ','On July 18, 2019 vide Corrigendum to Circular No.45/19/2018 dated May 30, 2018, CBIC has extended the tax period from March 18 to June 19 for filing refund application in respect of IGST paid on export of services & supplies made to SEZ. Press release has been issued to clarify the reason for such extension that registered persons have committed errors in declaring the details of the tax paid in Form GSTR-3B in respect of which refund was filed.','','','2019-07-20 07:10:31.349903','2019-07-20 07:15:40.479949',0,'tax_refund.jpg',1),(28,'More clarification issued for Goods sent/taken out of India for the purpose of exhibition or export promotion: PIB','On July 19, 2019 vide press release, CBIC in simplified language has explained the key points clarified in the Circular No. 108/27/2019 dated July 18, 2019 in respect of taxability & filing of refund claims of IGST paid in respect of goods taken out of India on consignment basis for the purpose of exhibition or other export promotion events.','','','2019-07-20 07:19:47.044329','2019-07-20 07:22:08.580177',0,'export_B7CVSY3.jpg',1),(29,'IGST paid on export which was rejected earlier due to wrong drawback code mentioned in shipping bills to be refunded','GST: Where assessee had exported certain goods to various countries on payment of integrated goods and services tax (IGST) through shipping bills and Competent Authority had not refunded IGST paid by assessee on account of wrong mentioning of drawback code in shipping bills, Competent Authority was directed to refund IGST paid on above goods','','','2019-07-22 06:04:29.886968','2019-07-22 06:05:47.470240',0,'tax_refund_BxbYdj1.jpg',1),(30,'RWA shall levy GST when the Annual Turnover & Monthly contribution are more than Rs. 20 lakhs & Rs. 7500','On July 22, 2019 vide Circular No. 109/28/2019 dated July 22, 2019, CBIC has clarified that if the annual turnover of RWA in a financial year does not exceed Rs. 20 lakhs then it is not required to pay GST even if the monthly contribution exceeds Rs. 7,500 per month per member. However, RWA shall be required to pay GST if such subscription is more than Rs. 7500/- per month per member and the annual turnover of RWA exceeds Rs. 20 Lakhs.','','','2019-07-22 13:18:48.034788','2019-07-22 13:21:19.831347',0,'gst_KpscGhm.jpg',1),(31,'Place of Supply In Case of Goods Which Are Installed or Assembled At Site','The GST Concept & Status document issued by the CBIC starts off with the following paragraph The introduction of Goods and Services Tax (GST) would be a very significant step in the field of indirect tax reforms in India. By amalgamating a large number of Central and State taxes into a single tax, it would mitigate cascading or double taxation in a major way and pave the way for a common national market.\nread more','','','2019-07-22 13:21:41.267490','2019-07-22 13:22:49.746237',0,'supply.jpg',1),(32,'GST would be levied on the total amount of contribution, if RWA charges more than Rs. 7,500 per month','GST : Where service by applicant, a registered housing society/resident welfare association to its members by way of reimbursement of charges or share of contribution, for outsourcing of goods or services from a third person for common use of its members, is such that it is above Rs. 7500 per month effective from 25-1-2018 (Rs.5000 before), it is not eligible for exemption from intra state supply of services of description of Sl. No. 77(c ) of Notification No. 12/2017-CT (Rate) dated 28-6-2017 as amended for CGST and Sl. No. 77(c ) of Notification No. II(2)/CTR/532(d-15)/2017 vide G.O.(Ms) No. 73 dated 29-6-2017 as amended for SGST. Thus, CGST and SGST at appropriate rates are to be paid by members on full amount of reimbursement of charges or share of contribution','','','2019-07-22 13:22:52.749567','2019-07-22 13:25:06.030629',0,'gst_2.jpg',1),(33,'No bar in GST on lodging FIR under Code of Criminal Procedure for an act which could be prosecuted under GST too','GST: Where Competent Authority had lodged an FIR against assessee under provisions of Code of Criminal Procedure, 1973 for offences punishable under provisions of Indian Penal Code alleging that assessee fraudulently obtained registration and assessee filed writ petition for quashing of FIR, there was no bar in Uttar Pradesh GST Act on lodging an FIR under Cr.PC for offences punishable under IPC even though, for same act/conduct, prosecution could be launched under U.P. GST Act and since impugned FIR disclosed commission of cognizable offences, it was not liable to be quashed','','','2019-07-23 05:56:25.086692','2019-07-23 05:58:18.563899',0,'gst_3.jpg',1),(34,'HC directed GST authorities to allow manual filing of TRAN-1 in case GST portal did not respond','GST : Where assessee had failed to upload Form GST TRAN-1 because of some technical difficulties, GST Council was directed to enable assessee to file said Form online and in case it was not possible to do so, GST Council would entertain concerned Form manually','','','2019-07-24 06:48:34.534111','2019-07-24 06:49:27.140063',0,'gst_Wdr0iiJ.jpg',1),(35,'Treatment of non-members as members of Co-operative society for GST exemption is outside AAR jurisdiction','GST : Advance Ruling Authority does not have jurisdiction to answer question whether members of society will be at par with other individual flat owners who are not members, hence, application for advance ruling is rejected, being non-maintainable','','','2019-07-24 06:49:49.433240','2019-07-24 06:52:43.689455',0,'gst_3_5jPAVuo.jpg',1),(36,'Online & Offline tendering is a supply of service','GST : Where applicant-Navi Mumbai Municipal Corporation caters to civic services to residents of city, and while developing various facilities for public at large it procures various services, goods from various contractors & vendor, which is awarded through tendering process which include Online Tendering & Offline Tendering (Manual Tendering), it is held that online tendering is not supply of goods but will be considered as Supply of Services. Offline tendering in its entirety involving sale of form, payment of tender fees and submission of bids etc. will be considered as supply of services. Online Tendering should get taxed under services heading 9997. Offline Tendering will be treated as supply of service under services heading 9997. Tendering will be covered under the residual services heading 9997','','','2019-07-24 06:53:33.544083','2019-07-24 06:55:35.299145',0,'gst_5.jpg',1),(37,'Cluster which is mounted on front end of motor vehicle is a part of motor vehicle, taxable @ 28% GST','GST : Where applicant, is engaged in Distribution of Veethree Range of Automotive Dashboard Instruments, Clusters and sensors which are mounted on front end of Cars, Trucks, Tractors, Two Wheelers, Three Wheelers Compressors etc., as also Stationary Engines, product sold by applicant i.e., cluster is part of motor vehicle and will be covered under Heading No. 8708 and is liable to tax at rate of 28 per cent (CGST - 14 per cent & SGST -14 per cent)','','','2019-07-24 06:56:12.329599','2019-07-24 06:57:15.780965',0,'6.jpg',1),(38,'Steel mug with a plastic outer body is to be treated as an article of steel, taxed @12% GST','GST : Steel mugs with a plastic outer body supplied by applicant would fall under Chapter Heading 7323, since the material which is giving the essential character to the steel cups with plastic body is presence of steel, which is 75 per cent of total value and composition of subject goods. Said product is therefore covered under Sl. No. 184 of Schedule II of Notification No. 1/2017 - Central Tax (Rate) dated 28-6-2017','','','2019-07-24 12:59:30.997333','2019-07-24 13:00:26.160792',0,'gst_hWz4i3h.jpg',1),(39,'Tips and Balls of Ball Point Pens are taxable @ 18% GST','GST : AAAR upheld order of WBAAR holding that \'Tips and Balls\' of Ball Point Pens are to be classified under GST Tariff Heading 9608 99 90 and included under Sl. No. 453 of Schedule III of Notification No. 01/2017 - Central Tax (Rate) dated 28-6-2017 and are taxable at rate of 18 per cent','','','2019-07-24 13:00:40.987197','2019-07-24 13:04:44.921516',0,'gst_3_rpv4Zb2.jpg',1),(40,'new news','body goes here','','','2019-07-25 05:40:38.247040','2019-07-25 05:40:38.247080',0,'',1),(41,'ITC availed on Input Services (remaining unutilized) would not be refunded on account of Inverted duty structure','GST : There is nothing in Rule 89 of CGST Rules, 2017, as amended by Notifications 21 and 26 of 2018, that overrides section 54 of the CGST Act, 2017 and they have to be read together harmoniously while granting refunds\n\nFacts\n\n The applicant formed with sole objective to bid and secure contract for design, engineering and construction of Long Bridge - Mumbai Trans Harbour Link project (\'MTHL Project\') has been awarded Package 2 of MTHL project.\n\n The MTHL Project entails procurement of various inputs, input services and capital goods such as cement, concrete, steel and steel structures, bridge accessories, formworks, plant and equipment, labour, etc. All such goods and services attract GST at varied rates, depending on the nature of such procurement. The ITC paid on the inputs and services are higher than output supply. Therefore, the transaction is covered under Inverted duty structure. In such cases as in the subject case, to avoid the cascading effect, Govt. has allowed relief in the form of Refund of unutilized Input tax Credit as provided in Section 54 .\n\n Applicant though eligible to claim for refund of inverted duty structure under Section 54(3) of the CGST Act, wishes to understand the in-principle applicability of Notification No 21/2018 - Central Tax (Rate) dated 18-4-2018 and Notification No. 26/2018-Central Tax dated 13-6-2018 in as much whether same allow for refund of ITC availed on input services (and remaining unutilized) in whole or part thereof.\n\nHeld\n\n There is nothing in Rule 89 of CGST Rules, 2017, as amended by Notifications 21 and 26 of 2018, that overrides section 54 of the CGST Act, 2017 and they have to be read together harmoniously while granting refunds.\n\n Both Notification No 21/2018 - Central Tax (Rate) dated 18-4-2018 and Notification No. 26/2018-Central Tax dated 13-6-2018 which prescribe method for carrying out provisions of section 54 (3), do apply to applicant and therefore do not allow refund of ITC availed on input services (and remaining unutilized) in whole or part thereof, in view of definition of \'input\' contained in section 2(59) and definition of \'Net ITC\' contained in Notification No. 26/2018-Central Tax dated 13-6-2018.','','','2019-07-26 06:09:58.835157','2019-07-26 06:14:19.128770',0,'tax_refund_Q3cmUPo.jpg',1),(42,'Plastic handles for motor vehicle doors to be treated as articles of plastic, taxable @ 18% GST','GST : Door-handle of motor vehicle, fittings made of plastic for motor vehicle\'s doors such as bracket, housing, bracket housing, stator, gasket etc. and glove box locking are all goods classifiable according to their constituent material in heading 3926, though, they are identifiable parts of automobiles','','','2019-07-26 06:14:42.958596','2019-07-26 06:15:57.038697',0,'gst_rK6ePAU.jpg',1),(43,'Security Services provided by the University imparting graduation courses & Ph.D programmes are taxable under GST','GST Security services provided by applicant to Deemed University (VNIT) is not exempt from GST, as exemption provided under Serial No. 66 of Notification No. 12/2017-Central Tax (Rate), dated 28-6-2017 is applicable to educational institution which provides services by way of pre-school education and education up to higher secondary school or equivalent\n\nFACTS\n\n Applicant-company is providing security services to an Institute (VNIT), which has been registered as deemed University by University Grants Commission. It seeks advance ruling on issue as to whether services provided to said Institute will qualify for exemption under Serial No. 66 of Notification No. 12/2017-Central Tax (Rate), dated 28-6-2017, considering it to be an educational institution.\n\nHeld\n\n AAR held that proviso to Sr. No. 66 of Notification No. 12/2017-Central Tax (Rate), dated 28-6-2017 very clearly states that only services provided to an educational institution which provides services by way of pre-school education and education up to higher secondary school or equivalent will be exempt. Since the applicant is not providing services, as an educational institution, by way of pre-school education and education up to higher secondary school or equivalent, security services provided in the present case will not be exempt from payment of GST. Further, AAR held that VNIT has neither been set up by an Act of Parliament or a State Legislature; nor has been established by any Government, with ninety per cent or more participation by way of equity or control, to carry out any function entrusted to a muncipality under article 243W of the Constitution or to a Panchayat under Article 243G of the Constitution and, hence, they cannot be considered as a \'Governmental Authority\'. Therefore, Sr. No. 3 of Notification No. 12/2017-Central Tax (Rate), dated 28-6-2017 is also not applicable in the subject case.','','','2019-07-26 06:16:24.932010','2019-07-26 06:18:49.948132',0,'gst_2_LyeAFiR.jpg',1),(44,'Society forming institute as joint project with Govt. to provide medical education is not educational institution','GST : Applicant society, not satisfying all criteria of an \'Educational Institution\', it would not remain out of scope of provisions of GST law\n\nFacts\n\n The applicant is registered as a Charitable Society with sole objective of attending health needs of rural India.\n\n Mahatma Gandhi Institute Of Medical Sciences (MGIMS) was established in 1969 as a joint project with an agreed arrangement for funding the said project by Govt. of India, Govt. of Maharashtra and applicant society in the ratio of 50:25:25 respectively. The Governing Council of MGIMS, as per University Statute comprises of Ten Members and a Chairman out of which, five Members are nominated by applicant and the remaining five Members are nominated by Central and State Governments.\n\n The applicant is seeking an Advance Ruling on whether the applicant, a Charitable Society having main object and factually engaged in imparting Medical Education, satisfying all criteria of \'Educational Institution\', can be said to be engaged in business so as to cast an obligation upon it to comply with provisions of CGST Act, 2017 and MGST Act, 2017 in totality and whether it is liable for registration under provisions of section 22?\n\nHeld\n\n It is found that the applicant and MGIMS can be considered as distinct persons since MGIMS is a joint project between applicant and State/Central Govts. Thus the educational services are seen to be rendered by MGIMS and not the applicant. Hence, the applicant cannot be said to be satisfying all the criteria of an \'Educational Institution\'.\n\n Scheme GST being a tax on the event of \'supply\' every supplier needs to get registered. However, as per the scheme of the Act, not every supplier is required to get registered. Only those suppliers, whose aggregate turnover of all supplies exceeds the threshold limit as prescribed under Section 22 (including exempted and taxable supplies).To be registered a person satisfies two conditions namely, supply of taxable goods or services or both and aggregate turnover in a financial year exceeds threshold limit. Thus, a person, whose aggregate turnover of all supplies is other than taxable supply, is not liable for registration. However, applicant has not given details of business conducted by it and therefore considering fact that it is MGIMS and not applicant who are imparting Medical Education, liability of applicant to obtain registration will depend on facts and circumstances of their business.','','','2019-07-26 06:19:05.915629','2019-07-26 06:21:18.714814',0,'book.jpg',1),(45,'Assessee to file representation to Nodal Officer for extension of time to submit Form GST Tran-1 electronically','GST: Where assessee had filed a writ petition for extending date of submitting declaration electronically in Form GST-TRAN-1 to avail benefit of input tax credit, assessee was directed to prefer a representation before GST Council as also before Nodal Officer for extending time for submitting Form GST-TRAN-1','','','2019-07-27 05:44:08.377866','2019-07-27 05:46:35.795985',0,'images.jpg',1),(46,'Services of water supply through tanker with help of GPRS system given to local authority are exempt from GST','GST : Contract entered in by applicant with NESL, a 100 per cent subsidiary of City Municipal Corporation, for providing services for management of non-network tanker with help of GPRS system would be exempt from GST since it falls under various exempt services in article 243W of constitution of India as well as services rendered to a local authority\n\n The applicant company was carrying on business as contractor comprising of dealership in computer hardware, software and peripherals and in service sector segment covering construction of IT Park, towing van activity. The applicant contractor was awarded a contract from NESL, a 100 per cent subsidiary of the City Municipal Corporation for providing services for the management of non-network tanker with the help of GPRS system in city and is currently providing the same that NESL, a SPV was specially set up by NMC for providing such types of services.\n\n This service was basically to provide water supply for domestic, industrial and commercial purposes at various locations in and around city. For this contract, the contractor was raising the bills on the NESL and was charging GST at the rate of 18 per cent in each bill.\n\n The applicant filed an instant application seeking an advance ruling in respect of the question that whether the contract from (NESL) for providing services for the management of non-network tanker with the help of GPRS system would be exempt from GST since it fell under the exempt services in the article 243W of the constitution of India as well as services rendered to a local authority.\n\n In the present case, NESL is established as per Nagpur Municipal Corporation Act, 1948 under section 58(B) and thereby permitting corporation to implement their duty allotted by the Government through this body i.e. NESL. Thus, from the perusal of Government Resolution and various definition i.e., government authority, government entity and local authority and MOU, it is found that NESL is an authority with the control or management with Municipal Fund. And as such NESL is a local authority as defined under section 2(69). In overall view, the applicant is providing pure services to local authority and is squarely covered by the Entry no. 3 of Notification No. 12/2017-CT (Rate) dated 28-6-2017.\n\n Thus, contract from (NESL) (a 100 per cent subsidiary of the city Municipal Corporation, for providing services for the management of non-network tanker with the help of GPRS system in city would be exempt from GST since it falls under the various exempt services in the article 243W of the constitution of India as well as services rendered to a local authority.','','','2019-07-27 05:46:55.109770','2019-07-27 05:48:08.197847',0,'jaar.jpg',1),(47,'Securities in GST regime  Ignoring investments might be risky','Goods and Services are two wide ambit term which encircle the entire universe in GST but excludes two terms  money and securities. The definition of \'goods\' and \'services\' in Section 2(52) and Section 2(102) of the Central goods and Services Tax Act, 2017 (CGST Act) specifically excludes money and securities respectively. While for Money,','','','2019-07-27 05:48:27.346385','2019-07-27 05:49:52.222094',0,'images_1.jpg',1),(48,'Calamity Cess in Kerala - Assessment','Kerala has become the first state to announce the flood cess as additional levy on Goods and Services Tax (GST) which has become a single tax levied on manufacture, sale and consumption of goods as well as services at the national level since its promulgation in 2016. The CPI (M)-led LDF government had announced the \"flood cess\" announced in the State Budget in February 2019 to mobilise additional revenue.','','','2019-07-27 05:49:57.561019','2019-07-30 10:13:06.342733',0,'GST-Cess-Taxscan.jpg',0),(49,'Semi-stitched Salwar/Churidar sets are garments taxed @ 5% if sale value is upto Rs. 1000 per piece otherwise @ 12%','GST : Where applicant-company, engaged in trading of readymade garments, fabrics and other similar items, seeks advance ruling on \'whether Salwar/Churidhar sets, comprising of three pieces of cloths viz., tops, Bottom and Dupatta, whether partially stitched/neck work done, or not would remain as \'fabrics\' under Chapters 50,52,54,55 based on constituent material and attract a total 5 per cent GST, since sets of three pieces consisting of unstitched Salwar (bottom), laced/hemmed/knotted duppata and Semi-stitched/Fully stitched Kurta (Top)/Top with defined neckline are \'garments\' and not mere \'fabric\', these are covered under specific entry in CTH 6211, as heading includes \'Salwars\' of various materials and as per Notification No. 01/2017-C.T. (Rate) dated 28-6-2017 as amended and Schedule I of Notification No. II(2)/CTR/532(d-4)/2017, subject goods are liable to GST at rate of 5 per cent [CGST - 2.5 per cent and SGST - 2.5 per cent], if Sale Value is less than Rs. 1000/- per piece and at rate of 12 per cent [CGST - 6 per cent and SGST - 6 per cent], if sale value is more than Rs. 1000/- per piece','','','2019-07-30 10:15:42.442991','2019-07-30 10:17:31.624606',0,'images_dU4zAv9.jpg',1),(50,'GST rates on Electric Vehicles reduced to 5% & various due dates extended by 36th GST Council Meeting','GST Council in its 36th Meeting held on July 27, 2019, has decided to reduce the rates on all Electric Vehicles from 12% to 5% and to extend the due date for making payment by the composition dealers for the first quarter, April - June, 2019 to August 31, 2019. Also, the due date to opt for 6% Composition scheme by the suppliers of services has been extended July 31, 2019 to September 30, 2019.','','','2019-07-30 10:17:47.305537','2019-07-30 10:20:38.009315',0,'car.jpg',1),(51,'HC allowed writ for fresh consideration where Single judge had not considered other grounds raised by assessee','GST : Where Assessing Authority issued on assessee a notice proposing refixation of payment of compounded tax under section 8(f) of Kerala VAT Act and assessee filed writ petition challenging impugned notice and also constitutional validity of section 174 of Kerala State GST Act and Single Judge of High Court dismissed petition holding that issue involved stood covered against assessee by virtue of judgment of Kerala High Court in case of Sheen Golden Jewels (India) (P.) Ltd. v. State Tax Officer [2019] 102 taxmann.com 208, since judgment in case of Sheen Golden Jewels (P.) Ltd. (supra) covered only question regarding validity of section 174 and Single Judge had omitted to consider other grounds raised in writ petition, writ petition required to be remitted to Single Judge for fresh consideration','','','2019-07-30 10:20:58.660028','2019-07-30 10:21:44.596514',0,'gst_xboCQis.jpg',1),(52,'Condonation of delay declined as assessee failed to provide sufficient cause of being prevented to file appeal on time','GST/Excise/ST/VAT : Where assessee, against order of Commissioner (Appeals) dated 30-4-2014, filed an appeal before Tribunal after a period of 4 years on 24-3-2018 with an application for condonation of delay stating that it vide letter dated 1-3-2018 intimated Superintendent of Central Excise that it had not received copy of order-in-appeal dated 30-4-2014 and requested to supply same to present appeal, since all notices right from 12-2-2007 were addressed at registered address of assessee and were received by it and appellate order dated 30-4-2014 was also served on same address and assessee failed to discharge onus that it was prevented by sufficient cause from filing appeal within limitation, Tribunal was justified in declining to condone delay','','','2019-07-30 10:22:22.387310','2019-07-30 10:23:51.453182',0,'images_OG65Qe5.jpg',1),(53,'Competent Authority to consider grievance of assessee to revise Tran-1 as ITC not transferred due to technical error','GST: Where assessee had duly filed Form GST TRAN-1 within prescribed time limit but no credit pertaining to closing balance of cenvat credit had been transferred to its Electronic Credit Ledger and thereafter assessee made numerous attempts to revise Form GST TRAN-1 but in vain and Competent Authority also disapproved request of assessee, request of assessee to revise Form GST TRAN-1 for first time could not be denied on technicalities and Competent Authority was directed to reconsider grievance of assessee','','','2019-07-30 10:24:08.905809','2019-07-30 10:25:07.512040',0,'gst_2_r8Bsup0.jpg',1),(54,'HC directed Competent Authority to release seized goods & vehicle on depositing tax & penalty by the assessee','GST : Where Competent Authority had seized goods of assessee under transport as well as vehicle and assessee\'s tax liability along with penalty was to tune of Rs. 1.44 lakhs, said authority was directed to release goods and vehicle on assessee depositing an amount of Rs. 1.44 lakhs with department','','','2019-07-30 10:25:42.739584','2019-07-30 10:28:00.052670',0,'tax_penaltyi.jpg',1),(55,'Coating of aluminium imported by the assessee to be classified under heading no. 3212 10 00 as \'stamping foil\'','GST/Excise/ST/VAT : Where assessee had imported coating of aluminium and claimed classification under Heading No. 7607 20 90, said product would be classifiable under Heading No. 3212 10 00 as stamping foil','','','2019-07-30 10:28:28.706267','2019-07-30 10:31:39.655297',0,'aluminium.jpg',1),(56,'Whether burden shared by captives comes under GST?','Interest subvention income are earnings received from the third party i.e. person other than the borrower. This scheme work as a compensation to the seller who intends to penetrate the market. They arrange low cost finance for their customers (though not low cost because the part of it is compensated by its captive unit).','','','2019-07-30 10:32:06.202163','2019-07-30 10:33:13.926537',0,'gst_b8K3IHD.jpg',1),(57,'Renting Warehouse : Not Immovable property ITC allowed?','The concept of renting warehouse has been in trend recently. Also, now the structures of the warehouse are flexible and referred as Pre-engineered warehouse which is nothing but a nut and bolt concept. This write up attempts to answer the issue of availing the input tax credit in case of renting of warehouse as general perception is of it being categorised as immovable property, however it is not the case.','','','2019-07-30 10:33:44.261931','2019-07-30 10:35:27.235376',0,'rent.png',1),(58,'Due date to opt for 6% Composition Scheme by filing CMP-02 has been extended to September 30, 2019','On July 29, 2019 vide Corrigendum to Circular No. 97/16/2019-GST, CBIC has amended the para 2(i) by extending the due date for filing intimation by persons who want to opt to pay tax at the rate of 6% under Composition Scheme in Form GST CMP-02 from July 31, 2019 to September 30, 2019.','','','2019-07-30 10:35:57.814399','2019-07-30 10:38:08.473507',0,'composition.jpg',1),(59,'Due date to make payment of taxes by Composition Dealers in form CMP-08 has been extended to August 31, 2019','On July 29, 2019 vide Notification No. 35/2019-Central Tax, CBIC has further extended the due date for making payment of taxes by Composition dealers in Form GST CMP-08 for the quarter April, 2019 to June, 2019 from July 31, 2019 to August 31, 2019.','','','2019-07-30 10:38:38.924043','2019-07-30 10:40:04.257731',0,'deadline.jpg',1),(60,'Money received by society from Co. for village development programme is a consideration for supply of service','GST : Where applicant-society, engaged in implementation of projects related to Corporate Social Responsibility (CSR), has signed a Memorandum of Understanding (MoU) with Agriculture Insurance Company of India Limited (AICL) for implementation of \'Integrated Village Development Programme\' for improving infrastructure facilities in 50 villages in States of Bihar, Jharkhand, Madhya Pradesh, Maharashtra and Uttar Pradesh, amount received by applicant from AICL is not in nature of grant-in-aid and is covered in definition of \'consideration\' for supply of goods or services under section 2(31) in respect of MoU and, hence, they are liable to pay GST under section 9(1)','','','2019-07-30 10:49:22.774522','2019-07-30 10:53:37.808991',0,'money.jpg',1),(61,'GST leviable on hotel accommodation services provided in foreign countries either as supplier or as agent','GST : Where applicant engaged in business of outbound tours and in providing reservation services for accommodation or services of booking of hotel rooms in foreign countries to Indian B2B (other travel agents and tour operators) and B2C (tourists) clients who are visiting overseas, has entered into contracts with various online/offline hotel aggregators for booking of hotel rooms in foreign countries and made payment to them on behalf of clients, since in respect of such services, applicant is covered in definition of \'Agent\', \'supplier\' and \'Taxable person\' under sections 2(5), 2(105) and 2(107) respectively of CGST Act, 2017, applicant is required to collect/deposit GST under section 9(1) of the CGST Act, 2017 on the amount received by them from clients on value of \'hotel accommodation\' service','','','2019-07-30 10:54:03.821571','2019-07-30 10:56:16.355208',0,'hotel.jpg',1),(62,'Implication of GST w.r.t works contract tendered before & after 01.07.2017 has been considered in Schedule of Rate','GST : From Schedule of Rate, it was evident that implications of GST on contract works executed after coming into force of GST had been considered, hence it could not be said that petitioners were being made liable to pay GST without any mechanism provided for same\n\nFacts\n\n Tenders were floated prior to coming into force of Act of 2017 and in respect thereof agreement i.e. Standard Bidding Document (SBD) applicable in Works Departments of Government of Bihar contains Clause 35 which deals with condition of reimbursement of levy/taxes if levied after receipt of tenders.\n\n Petitioners moved instant court stating that they had participated in tender process prior to coming into force of the GST Act, 2017, when Bihar VAT Act, 2005 was in force and applicable in relation to contracts in question.\n\n According to petitioners, after coming into force of GST Act, 2017 it was incumbent upon Works Department of the Government of Bihar to suitably amend Clause \'35\' of conditions for reimbursement of levy/taxes if levied after receipt of tenders, as in absence of suitable amendments thereof, petitioners were being made liable to pay GST without there being any provision for reimbursement of liabilities falling upon them by virtue of implementation of GST Act, 2017.\n\nHeld\n\n From Schedule of Rate (SOR) brought on record showing contract value arrived at in a work tendered prior to 1-7-2017 (pre-GST) and one SOR of work tendered after 1-7-2017 (post-GST), implication of \'GST\' had been considered. After treating effect of \'GST\' total basic rate applicable after coming into force of \'GST\' had been fixed and petitioners as well as State agree with formulation of SOR taking note of effect of GST. Thus, issue as regards implications of GST on contract works executed after coming into force of GST having been considered, it was to be held that grievance of petitioners had in fact been addressed.','','','2019-07-30 10:56:41.713051','2019-07-30 11:01:31.264915',0,'under_cons.jpg',1),(63,'Competent Authority to release assessee on bail where 57 days were over since his arrest for offence committed in GST','GST: Where Competent Authority had arrested assessee for an offence punishable under clauses (b) and (c) of section 132 of Central Goods and Services Tax Act, 2017 and 57 days were over since his arrest, assessee was released on bail','','','2019-07-30 11:01:51.325262','2019-07-30 11:04:00.125498',0,'image_-.jpg',1),(64,'Commissionerate to issue certificate after verifying ITC availed through Tran-1 but not reflected in credit ledger: HC','GST: Where assessee filed writ petition stating that credit of duties for period prior to 1-7-2017 though reflected in declaration filed in Form GST TRAN-1 was not shown in electronic credit ledger account and due to this it was unable to avail such credit, Gujarat Commissionerate was directed to verify credit availed by assessee and issue a certificate in this regard','','','2019-08-01 06:36:15.797610','2019-08-01 06:42:33.028981',0,'input_tax_credit.jpg',1),(65,'Fan coil unit is a part of Air Conditioning System, taxable @ 28% GST','GST : Product Fan coil unit (FCU) would be covered under HSN Code 8415 and not 8418\n\n The appellant was carrying on a business of supply of products such as fan coil units, valves, actuator, thermostat etc. along with its standard spare parts and accessories to its various customers. The appellant had filed an application for advance ruling on the question that whether the fan coil unit was covered under HSN Code 8418.\n\n The AAR held that the impugned item i.e., \'fan coil unit\' would be covered under the HSN code 8415 instead 8418 as claimed by the appellant.\n\n In instant appeal the appellant contended that fan coil units, standalone, could be classified in appropriate sub-heading of CTH-8414 which specifically covers fans and could not be classified in CTH 8415.\n\n It is contended by the appellant that the FCU would be covered by CTH 8418 as they are used along with the chillers and chillers are classified under heading 8418. They have referred to the explanatory note 2(b) of section XVI. As per 2(b) if parts are used with a particular kind of machine then it shall be classified with a machine of that kind only. The contention of the appellant could not be agreed with as it is clear from the description of the product that FCUs are used in the air conditioning unit and not in refrigerating unit and therefore they cannot be covered under heading 8418. The other contention of the appellant is that stand alone FCUs should be classified under CTH 8414 which specifically cover fans.\n\n It is easily seen from the description that the Fan described under 8414 do not at all have any resemblance with a FCU. Therefore, there is no reason to believe that FCU will be covered by heading 8414.','','','2019-08-01 06:50:54.488864','2019-08-01 06:51:52.118427',0,'107466.jpg',1),(66,'Services provided under an agreement which could also be performed independently are mixed supplies','GST : Respondent AK India, a subsidiary of AK Japan provides sales promotion and marketing support services to AK group. It has entered into a services agreement with AK Japan wherein it provides to its holding company following services, corporate accounting, corporate finance, corporate personnel and labour relations, corporate research and development, quality assurance and corporate intellectual property etc. It is observed that respondent is undertaking a gamut of activities which are in nature of accounting services having SAC 9982 and other professional, technical and business services having SAC 9983, which are specified under section 8 of chapter 99 having description Business and Production services\n\n Since all these activities undertaken by respondent could have been performed separately and independently with each other, fact that respondent is raising a singly consolidated invoice in accordance with service agreement makes these supplies stipulated under this agreement as mixed supply in terms of provision of section 2(74).','','','2019-08-01 06:52:08.365822','2019-08-01 06:53:17.737748',0,'gst_.jpg',1),(67,'Brewing, bottling & packaging of liquor undertaken on behalf of manufacturer constitutes job work, taxed @ 18% GST','GST : Where appellant company has entered into agreement with PIL to brew/manufacture, package and supply Products, as specified under agreement, from its bottling unit to buyers / distributors in territory identified by appellant, since, entire gamut of activities viz.- brewing, bottling and packaging of alcoholic liquor is undertaken by PIL at behest of appellant, as per agreement entered between PIL and appellant, wherein, cost of purchase of entire raw materials and other inputs is also incurred to appellant and appellant also bears cost of insurance in respect of materials, Products and work in process, it will constitute job work and accordingly, will attract 18 per cent GST','','','2019-08-01 06:53:20.702081','2019-08-01 06:54:05.603032',0,'',1),(68,'Supply of ElectroInk along with consumables to be used in printing press machine is mixed supply','GST : Where all imaging products i.e. ElectroInk and others like developer and plates supplied by appellant are equally important to complete supply and no one of them is principal supply, supply of ElectroInk with other consumables is a mixed supply as defined under section 2(74) and is also a continuous supply as defined under section 2(32)','','','2019-08-01 06:54:28.210519','2019-08-01 06:55:03.466237',0,'107470.jpg',1),(69,'Marketing services to facilitate sale of software of holding Co. are composite supplies of intermediary services','GST : Where applicant-company is facilitating process for sale of CRS software belonging to their foreign parent company, to Indian subscribers, and all marketing and promotional activities, viz. advertising, PR, Sponsorships, any special events and trade shows etc. are solely aimed to create customer base for parent company, to augment its business in India, by way of identifying and potential subscribers and thereby enhancing business opportunities for parent company, since by carrying out all activities as per said agreement, appellant is arranging as well as facilitating supply of services between parent company and potential subscribers and thus, activities undertaken by appellant are primarily in nature of those of intermediary, entire spectrum of activities undertaken by appellant can be considered as composite supply in term of provision of section 2(30) as all activities of appellant are carried out in conjunction with each other and can be naturally bundled in ordinary course of business as all activities performed viz. -advertising, PR, promotional activities, Sponsorship, Trade shows, demonstrating offerings, etc., by appellant are intended to identify potential subscriber - However, principal supply of appellant is that of intermediary and all these mentioned activities can either be considered either as ancillary or incidental to principal service\n\n Further, the AAAR does not have jurisdiction to decide place of supply of service as question regarding determination of supply of goods or services or both is not mentioned in section 97(2).','','','2019-08-01 06:55:20.082416','2019-08-01 06:55:59.502106',0,'107467.jpg',1),(70,'Services by way of giving Electric vehicles on hire to local authority are now exempted from GST','On July 31, 2019 vide Notification No. 13/2019-Central Tax (Rate), Central government has exempted electrically operated vehicles designed to carry more than 12 passengers given on hire to a local authority from GST by amending Notification No. 12/2017-Central Tax (Rate) dated June 28, 2017.','','','2019-08-01 06:57:22.264981','2019-08-01 06:58:21.629570',0,'BNSNews301082019.jpg',1),(71,'Supply of Electric Vehicles including two & three wheelers, shall be subject to 5% GST','On July 31, 2019 vide Notification No. 12/2019-Central Tax (Rate), Central government has notified the GST rate of 5% for electric vehicles including two/three wheelers and charger or charging station for such vehicles by amending Notification No. 1/2017-Central Tax (Rate) dated June 28, 2017. This notification shall come in to force from August 1, 2019.','','','2019-08-01 06:58:37.899320','2019-08-01 06:59:14.001542',0,'',1),(72,'Supply of Electric Vehicles including two & three wheelers, shall be subject to 5% GST','On July 31, 2019 vide Notification No. 12/2019-Central Tax (Rate), Central government has notified the GST rate of 5% for electric vehicles including two/three wheelers and charger or charging station for such vehicles by amending Notification No. 1/2017-Central Tax (Rate) dated June 28, 2017. This notification shall come in to force from August 1, 2019.','','','2019-08-02 10:54:52.303352','2019-08-02 10:58:05.684145',0,'BNSNews501082019.png',1),(73,'Penalty recovered by finance company due to delay in payment of EMI by borrowers is taxable under GST','GST : Penal charges / penalty recovered by appellant finance company from their borrowers on account of delay in payment of EMI by borrowers are adequately covered under clause 5 (e) of Schedule II of the CGST Act and will attract GST','','','2019-08-02 10:58:09.607478','2019-08-02 10:58:43.699391',0,'108001.png',1),(74,'Supply of food at events organized in the club premises is taxable @ 18% GST','GST: Where applicant was engaged in providing its members privileges and amenities such as supply of food from restaurant, other services provided in restaurant like booking of personal dining area, supply of food at events organised in club premises likeget-togethers and parties hosted by members of club, etc., supply of food at events organised by appellant in club premises was taxable under serial no. 7(v) of Notification No. 11/2017-Central Tax (Rate) dated 28-06-2017 under Central Goods and Services Tax Act, 2017 & Notification No. 1135-FT dated 28-06-2017 under West Bengal Goods and Services Tax Act, 2017 and taxed at rate of 18 per cent\n\n The applicant stated to be a non-profit making company, was engaged in providing its members privileges and amenities such as swimming facility, gymnasium, indoor games, restaurant service, etc. The various services provided by assessee were supply of food from restaurant, other services provided in restaurant like booking of personal dining area, supply of food at events organised in the club premises likeget-togethers and parties hosted by members of the club, supply of other services being part of organising the get-togethers and parties in the club premises like valet parking charge, decoration charge, music charges. Etc., and other services provided by the club.\n\n The WBAAR observed that the appellant\'s services could be broadly classified into two categories, namely, supply of food, by way or as part of the services provided at its restaurant or at social events organised in the club premises and the other services to the members and the guests that are not bundled with the supply of food and were charged separately. The WBAAR further observed that the supply of food, by way or as part of any service or any other manner whatever, was a composite supply. It pronounced its advance ruling that the supply of food, by way or as part of any service or any other manner whatever, from the appellant\'s restaurant were classifiable under SAC 9963 and taxable under S1. No. 7(i) or7(iii) of the Notification no. 11/20l7-C.T (Rate)dated 28-06-2017 under the Central Goods and Services Tax Act, 2017 &Notification No. 1135-FTdated 28-06-2017 under the West Bengal Goods and Services Tax Act, 2017. If food was supplied by way of or as a part of the services associated with or ganisation of social events at the club premises, it would be classifiable under SAC 9963 and taxable under Sl. no. 7(vii) of the Rate Notification. All other services offered by the appellant were classifiable under SAC 9995 and taxable under Sl. no. 33 of the Rate Notification.\n\n The appellant had filed an instant appeal against the above advance ruling on grounds that food supplied for social gatherings could not be categorised as composite services and taxable at the rate of 18 percent. The club raised separate bills for food and beverages for social gatherings. Further, as per the rate notification all restaurant services were to be taxed at the rate of 5 percent with no input tax credit.\n\n Under the provisions of serial no. 7(v) of the Rate Notification it is seen that any supply of food or beverage at any event, whether or not served at an outdoor or an indoor function, squarely falls under the said category. A social get-together held at the club premises as explained by the appellant, is \"an event or a function\" of occasional nature. An \"event\" is a planned public or social occasion whereas, a \"function\" means an official ceremony or a formal social event, such as a party or a special meal, at which a lot of people are usually present. The provisions of serial no.7(v) of the Rate Notification is not restricted to exhibition halls or marriage halls and includes all indoor and outdoor functions. Unlike the provisions of serial no. 7(vii) of the Rate Notification there is no restrictive clause as to rental of the premises where the event is being held. Further the phrase, \"outdoor/indoor functions that are event based and occasional in nature\' includes all functions which are occasional by nature irrespective of whether these are held indoor or outdoor. The qualifying criteria are that firstly, it must be an event based function and secondly, it must be occasional in nature. The social get-togethers and parties are special social functions and definitely occasional in nature. The services provided by the club at these social get-togethers are not regular restaurant services as envisaged from the submissions made by the appellant. So, the food supplied at events which are occasional in nature like the social get-togethers arranged at the club premises will unambiguously fall under serial no. 7(v) of the rate notification.\n\n In view of above discussion it is held that supply of food at events organised by the appellant in the club premises is taxable under serial no. 7(v) of the Notification No. 11/2017-Central Tax (Rate) dated 28-06-2017 under the Central Goods and Services Tax Act, 2017 & Notification No. 1135-FT dated 28-06-2017 under the West Bengal Goods and Services Tax Act, 2017 and taxed at the rate of 18 per cent. There is no other infirmity in the order of the WBAAR considering the written and oral submission of the appellant.','','','2019-08-02 10:59:01.852343','2019-08-02 10:59:39.729517',0,'108004.jpg',1),(75,'First Audit Report of CAG (Indirect Taxes-GST) for the year ended March 2019 has been issued','The gaps / shortcomings have been pointed out in the spirit of constructive suggestions to realize the full potential of this major reform in the first Audit Report of CAG on Goods and Services Tax (GST), prepared on the basis of audits conducted during the year. The Report acknowledges the magnitude of the tax reform under GST and the efforts of all the stakeholders, including the businesses, in transiting to this system.','','','2019-08-02 11:00:02.274151','2019-08-02 11:00:37.332001',0,'BNSNews601082019_1.jpg',1),(76,'GST leviable on cheque bouncing charges collected from borrowers on account of dishonouring of cheques','GST : Where Appellant (Bajaj Finance) non-banking financial company engaged in providing various types of loans, enters into agreements with borrower/customers for providing interest bearing loans to them and loan agreements provide for repayment of outstanding dues/Equated Monthly Installments (EMI) through cheque/Electronic Clearing System (\'ECS\')/National Automated Clearing House (\'NACH\') bounce charges, collected by appellant from their customers/borrowers in event of dishonouring of cheques issued by them or failure of payment through ECS and other electronic means due to non availability of sufficient funds in borrower\'s/customer\'s bank account, would attract GST as appellant has tolerated act, or situation of default by borrowers of loan, against some fixed amount/charges agreed to be paid by borrowers and this very activity of appellant viz. tolerating act, or situation of default by borrowers, is adequately covered under provisions of entry 5(e) of Schedule II to CGST Act, 2017 and, thus, amounts to supply of service in accordance with provision of section 7(1)(d) of CGST Act, 2017','','','2019-08-02 11:00:51.327024','2019-08-02 11:01:30.913518',0,'108006.jpg',1),(77,'Total GST collection for July 2019 was Rs. 1,02,083 crore','GST collection in July, 2018 was Rs. 96,483 crore. The GST collection during July, 2019 had shown a growth of 5.80% over the GST collection in the same month last year.','','','2019-08-02 11:01:46.009961','2019-08-02 11:02:26.715705',0,'BNSNEWS02082019.jpg',1),(78,'Competent Authority to take decision on preliminary objections raised by assessee against SCN rejecting refund claim','GST : Where Competent Authority had rejected refund claim of assessee and thereafter issued a show cause notice on assessee for payment of tax along with interest and penalty and assessee filed preliminary objections to show cause notice, but no response had been received till date, said authority was directed to take a decision on preliminary objections by passing a speaking order','','','2019-08-02 11:02:42.081569','2019-08-02 11:03:26.272114',0,'107145.jpg',1),(79,'Clarifications issued on refund of IGST paid on import in case of United Nations or other International Organizations','On August 1, 2019 vide Circular No. 23/2019-Customs, CBIC has clarified refund mechanism of IGST paid on imports by specialized agencies of the United Nations Organization or a specified international organization shall be entitled to claim refund of central taxes paid on the supplies of goods or services received by them.','','','2019-08-02 11:03:28.565795','2019-08-02 11:04:03.109896',0,'',1),(80,'GST Delhi North Commissionerate busts fake GST invoices worth Rs. 137 crores: PIB','On August 2, 2019 vide Press Release, Ministry of Finance has reported that Central GST Delhi North Commissionerate has busted a racket of issuance of fake GST invoices amounting to Rs. 137 crores. The accused were operating fake firms without actual supply of goods and services in order to pass on fraudulent ITC. The accused have been arrested and investigations are going on to identify other individuals and firms involved in this racket.','','','2019-08-05 06:31:44.668347','2019-08-05 06:33:34.446822',0,'gst_invoice.png',1),(81,'Issues In GST Annual Return System','Introduction\n\nIn this article, we will discuss about the issues in relation to GST Annual Return filing procedures and systems for the Financial Year 2017-18.\n\n1. The Chapter IX of CGST Act deals with the various Returns to be filed under the GST regime. As per this chapter, a registered person is required to file mainly below Statements / Returns periodically as well as on annual basis:\n\ni.	 	Statement of outward supplies i.e. GSTR 1 (Section 37)\nii.	 	Statement of inward supplies i.e. GSTR 2 (Section 38)\niii.	 	Return i.e. GSTR 3 (Section 39)\niv.	 	Form GSTR 3B [Rule 61(5)]\nv.	 	Annual return i.e. Form GSTR 9 (Section 44)\nvi.	 	Final Return i.e. GSTR 10 (Section 45)\nvii.	 	First return (Section 40)\nAll of the above statements, returns are to be filed based on the self-assessment by the registered person. The Statement of outward supplies u/s 37 and Form GSTR 3B are currently being filed by the registered persons on monthly / quarterly basis. However, Statement of inward supplies u/s 38 and Return u/s 39 are on hold.\n\nRequirement of Annual Return\n\n2. Section 44 of CGST Act provides that every registered person, except few categories, are required to file annual return apart from periodical returns filed during the year. The categories who are not required to file Annual Return are as under:\n\ni.	 	Input Service Distributor (ISD)\nii.	 	A person paying tax u/s 51 of CGST Act\niii.	 	A person paying tax u/s 52 of CGST Act\niv.	 	Casual taxable Person\nv.	 	Non-resident Taxable Person\nThe Annual return for a particular financial year in Form GSTR 9 is required to be filed on or before 31st December of next financial Year. However, for FY 2017-18, the due date of filing annual return is extended up to 31st August 2019. Further, registered person who is required to get his accounts audited u/s 35(5) of CGST Act having annual aggregate turnover more than two crores during a financial year is to file GSTR 9 electronically along with a copy of audited annual accounts and a Reconciliation Statement in Form GSTR 9C. The most important thing is that the reconciliation of annual return is to be done with the books of accounts of a particular State.\n\nIssues\n\n3. The global best practice is not to have annual return concept in indirect tax system. The GST is a new and dynamic tax system. This anomaly may have been removed or not inserted in the GST law by adopting global benchmark of indirect tax practices. The concept of having annual return is basically in the Direct Tax laws and not under indirect tax laws\n\n4. The business is required to prepare and maintain state-wise books of accounts separately for each State having separate GST registration despite of consolidated books of accounts on global / pan India level. It is a cumbersome and tedious task. It requires a lot of time and efforts in preparing separate Trial Balance, Profit & Loss Accounts and Trading Accounts. Moreover, segregating State wise assets / fixed assets or immovable properties is a challenge for the reconciliation purposes. Businesses are facing difficulties.\n\n5. The annual return is basically a consolidation of full year\'s data of supplies, procurements, input tax credit taken, taxes payable, taxes paid, late fees, particulars of demands and refunds etc. This may be considered as a duplicacy due to disclosure of same figure in two separate returns at two different times except disclosure of left out transactions. The instructions to Annual Return Form GSTR 9 says that it is mandatory to file all Form GSTR 1 and Form GSTR 3B for FY 2017-18 before filing GSTR 9. This is again creating hurdles for those companies who could not file Form 3B due to any reason including financial distress.\n\n6. The instruction of GSTR 9 says that additional liability for FY 2017-18 may be declared in this return. Further, it mandates to pay additional liability in cash only i.e. from Electronic Cash Ledger. It means the tax payer cannot pay any additional liability arising out of GSTR 9 return by using input tax credit from Electronic Cash Ledger. This provision is very harsh and is totally against the spirit of GST law.\n\n7. Any left out input tax credit cannot be claimed through GSTR 9. However, additional liability has to be paid, that too in cash. This is against the natural law of justice.\n\n8. The GSTR 2A figure generated as on 1st May 2019 shall be auto populated in table 8A. Now the issue is that those registered persons who had not submitted their returns up to 30th April 2019, their ITC will not be reflected in GSTR 2A of the recipient. There were several cases, where return were saved but not filed till the 30th April 2019.\n\n9. HSN wise summary of outward and inward supplies are to be provided along with quantitative details. Showing quantitative details are a herculean task in itself. It requires reconciliation of each goods having different HSN up to four digit level. However, for inward supplies, there is relaxed norms for disclosure of HSN wise summary in Annual return table 18. The summary details are required for only those inward supplies whose value are 10% or more of total inward supplies during the year.\n\n10. Disclosure of ITC details includes showing all the inward supplies under the three categories i.e. inputs, input services and capital goods. This is a big challenge for the entities who are not using good ERP system or operating on small accounting systems or accounting manually. Many ERP systems are still not customized for this kind of disclosures.\n\n11. The information of inward supplies received from composition taxpayers needs to be shown separately in Table 16 of GSTR 9. This is almost impossible to segregate this data from the pool of details by any taxpayer.\n\nConclusion\n\n12. From the above said issues, it is evident that the provisions related to GST Annual Return are not suitable to the industry in its current form. However, we expect some clarifications from the CBIC in this regard. The taxpayers should be well guided by the tax experts / professionals to fill up the FORM GSTR 9 correctly to ensure GST compliances. The policy makers in Government should also consider to abolish requirement of Annual Return filing under the GST regime and adopt the best indirect tax practices prevailing across the World.','','','2019-08-05 06:43:51.708774','2019-08-05 06:47:35.358414',0,'gst_return.jpg',1),(82,'Treatment of sale promotion schemes under GST','Every business has a marketing and sales plan in order to increase sales volume, attract new customers and achieve its business objectives. Sales promotion schemes are the key drivers to supplement, co-ordinate and achieve functional objectives.','','','2019-08-05 06:48:07.100525','2019-08-05 06:49:26.008946',0,'goods_and_service.jpg',1),(83,'HC directed Competent Authority to release seized goods on furnishing of bank guarantee by assessee','GST : Where Competent Authority had seized goods of assessee under transport and also imposed penalty under section 129(3) and assessee filed writ petition challenging penalty order, against penalty order assessee had an efficacious remedy under section 107 of filing an appeal\n\nGST : Where Competent Authority had seized goods of assessee under transport and also imposed penalty under section 129(3), said authority was directed to release goods on assessee furnishing bank guarantee','','','2019-08-06 05:34:12.743028','2019-08-06 05:35:37.272386',0,'bank_grantee.jpg',1),(84,'ITC can be availed on full GST charged on undiscounted supply invoice of goods/services issued by supplier','GST : AAAR sets aside ruling of AAR and holds that where a post purchase discount is extended by supplier of goods or services to appellant MRF Ltd. on account of their registering in interactive automated data exchange arrangement setup by C2FO India LLP, appellant can avail Input Tax Credit of full GST charged on undiscounted supply invoice of goods/ services by their suppliers. A proportionate reversal of credit is not required to be done by them. This is subject to their fulfilling other conditions stipulated by law and that GST paid by them for said goods/service is not reversed or reimbursed/ re-credited etc. to them in any manner by supplier or on his behalf, after credit has been availed by MRF\n\n[MRF Ltd., In re [2019] 103 taxmann.com 278 (AAR - TAMILNADU) - Set aside]','','','2019-08-06 05:35:53.546472','2019-08-06 05:37:04.676885',0,'gst_..png',1),(85,'ITC not available on cranes given on hire from H.O. to branch where payments are netted off against receivables','GST : Where applicant-SML is engaged in business of providing medium-sized heavy-duty cranes on rental/lease/hire basis to its clients without transferring right to use cranes and IGST is payable on inter-State movement of cranes by supplier (i.e., SML Maharashtra) to recipient office of SML (i.e. SML Tamil Nadu, applicant) duly registered under GST receiving such cranes for further supply on hire charges, it was held that on supply received from SML, Maharashtra, applicant SML, Tamil Nadu, is not eligible for full input tax credit but only to extent specified in restrictions as per second proviso to section 16(2) of CGST Act and Rule 37 of CGST Rules, read with section 20(iv) of IGST Act, subject to fulfillment of all other conditions under section 16 of CGST Act, read with section 20(iv) of IGST Act','','','2019-08-06 05:37:23.686528','2019-08-06 05:38:26.049493',0,'payment.jpg',1),(86,'Wet Wipes are taxable @ 28% GST up to 14-11-2017 & @ 18% GST from 15-11-2017','GST : Product \'Wet Wipes\' supplied by applicant is classifiable under Heading No. 3307 90 90 of First Schedule to Customs Tariff Act, 1975 and rate of tax applicable is 14 per cent CGST and 14 per cent SGST as per Sl. No. 29 of Schedule IV of Notification No. 1/2017-Central Tax (Rate), dated 28-6-2017 and as per Sl. No. 29 of Schedule IV of Notification No. II(2)/CTR/532 (d-4)/2017 vide G.O. (Ms) No. 62, dated 29-6-2017, respectively upto 14-11-2017. From 15-11-2917, applicable tax rate is 9 per cent CGST and 9 per cent SGST as per Sl. No. 60A of Schedule III of Notification No. 1/2017-Central Tax (Rate), dated 28-6-2017 as amended and as per Sl. No. 60A of Schedule III of Notification No. II(2)/CTR/532(d-4)/2017 vide G.O.(Ms) No. 62, dated 29-6-2017 as amended, respectively','','','2019-08-06 05:38:41.581344','2019-08-06 05:39:36.800073',0,'a.jpg',1),(87,'Taxing out the ITeS sector!!','The government, on July 18, 2019, issued a Circular (No. 107/26/2019-GST), seeking to clarify issues around export status under the GST law, for operations undertaken by ITeS companies in India.','','','2019-08-06 05:39:49.900002','2019-08-06 05:40:57.864021',0,'tax.jpg',1),(88,'Probing the Fate of Input Tax Credit on Normal Loss','It is commonly seen across industries that a certain percentage of input is lost/destroyed in its normal course of activities and thus, becomes unavailable for supply, either directly or indirectly. This has created much conjecture on treatment of input tax credit already availed by the registered supplier on the portion of input that has been lost/destroyed. In light of the above circumstance, a pragmatic analysis has been drawn here under.','','','2019-08-06 05:43:20.259306','2019-08-06 05:43:55.834647',0,'',1),(89,'Value of goods in case of inter-state supply by H.O. to branch office shall be open market value under GST','GST : Value in respect of supply of goods i.e., lenses, frames, sun glasses, contact lenses as well as reading glasses, complete spectacles by applicant to distinct persons being branches outside state for further supply as such by recipient would be open market value of such supplies that was available as per rule 28(a) and explanation (a) to chapter IV of CGST/TNGST Rules 2017 read with section 15 of the CGST/TNGST Act, 2017 and applicant had option to adopt an amount equivalent to ninety per cent of price charged for supply of goods of like kind and quality by recipient to his customer not being a related person\n\n The applicant was trading spectacle frames, lens, sunglasses and accessories which were procured locally or imported. It had its office in Tamil Nadu. The goods transferred as such to its branches in other states outside who further sold to their customers. The applicant stated that it was eligible under second proviso to rule 28 of Valuation Rules/CGST Rules under which it could declare any value in the invoice of transfer to other related party. It also stated that it was covered under CGST rule 28(a) as the open market value was shown, but it wanted to use proviso 2 and not proviso 1. It stated that both proviso should not be read together and were independent.\n\n The question relates to determination of value to be adopted in respect of transfer to branches located outside the State, i.e., to distinct persons of the same PAN.\n\n Under GST, branches which are situated outside the state are treated as distinct person. In the above case the supply between the applicant and the branches is considered as a supply between distinct persons, the fact of which is not disputed by the applicant also. The value to be adopted is governed by rules prescribed as per section 15(4).\n\n The value in respect of supply of goods i.e. lenses, frames, sun glasses, contact lenses as well as reading glasses, complete spectacles by the applicant to distinct persons being branches outside the state of Tamil Nadu shall be the open market value of such supplies that is available as per of rule 28(a) and Explanation (a) to chapter IV of CGST/TNGST Rules 2017 read with section 15 of the CGST/TNGST Act 2017. Where the goods are intended for further supply as such by the recipient and the applicant has the option to adopt an amount equivalent to ninety per cent of the price charged for the supply of goods of like kind and quality by the recipient to his customer being a related person as the value of such supplies to the distinct recipient as per proviso to rule 28) and explanation (a) and (b) to chapter IV of CGST/TNGST rules 2017 read with section 15 of the CGST/TNGST Act 2017.','','','2019-08-06 05:44:08.340672','2019-08-06 05:45:15.588851',0,'gst_tax.jpg',1),(90,'Assessee to furnish pending returns before competent Authority for revocation of cancellation of GST registration','GST: Where Competent Authority had cancelled registration of assessee for not furnishing returns well within time from October, 2018 to April, 2019, assessee was directed to submit relevant returns before Competent Authority, who would consider same and cancellation of registration could be revoked in terms of section 30','','','2019-08-06 05:45:33.893436','2019-08-06 05:46:39.081444',0,'gst_registration.jpg',1),(91,'Assessee to furnish pending returns before competent Authority for revocation of cancellation of GST registration','GST: Where Competent Authority had cancelled registration of assessee for not furnishing returns well within time from October, 2018 to April, 2019, assessee was directed to submit relevant returns before Competent Authority, who would consider same and cancellation of registration could be revoked in terms of section 30','','','2019-08-07 06:31:52.282090','2019-08-07 06:32:47.066088',0,'',1),(92,'Medicaments containing prebiotic & probiotic supplements, oral rehydration formulae and tonic are taxable @ 18% GST','GST : Where appellant is manufacturer of pharmaceuticals, active pharmaceutical ingredients (APIs), medicaments, etc., products in question like Folcovit capsule, Lecolite Z sachet are not eligible for drug license under Drugs and Cosmetics Act, 1940 as these are mainly prebiotic and probiotic supplements, oral rehydration formulae and tonic and, therefore, same are rightly are classified under Heading No. 2106, and taxable @ 18 per cent GST\n\nCase Review:\n\nEskag Pharma (P.) Ltd., In re [2019] 103 taxmann.com 434 (AAR - West Bengal) affirmed.','','','2019-08-07 06:32:51.659105','2019-08-07 06:34:26.397818',0,'medicament.jpg',1),(93,'Is the Constitutional Amendment in Article 370 has any Implications on Income Tax Act & GST Act?','On 5 August 2019, the Honble Union Home Minister Sh. Amit Shah has moved a resolution to amend Article 370 of the Constitution of India in the Rajya Sabha, so as to do away with some of the privileges of special autonomous status being granted to the State of Jammu & Kashmir by the said Article 370 and to reorganize the State of Jammu & Kashmir into two separate Union Territories i.e. Jammu and Kashmir and Ladakh.','','','2019-08-07 06:34:40.094275','2019-08-07 06:35:23.544329',0,'',1),(94,'Notice issued on bank to pay assessee\'s GST interest liability to be set aside, if such payment was made by assessee','GST : Where assessee for period from July, 2017 to November, 2018 was unable to pay entire tax due on due date and Competent Authority issued on assessee a notice under section 50 calling upon it to pay interest on delayed payment of tax and further issued a notice under section 79 on assessee\'s bank asking it to make payment in pursuance of aforesaid demand, if assessee would make payment of admitted liability on or before 20-6-2019, notice issued on assessee\'s bank will stand set aside','','','2019-08-13 08:50:46.997893','2019-08-13 08:52:26.263185',0,'gst_7.jpg',1),(95,'Waiver of condition for hearing of appeal by an Appellate Authority - Whether permissible?','The right of appeal, invariably in all fiscal statutes including some of the non-taxing statutes, has been made a conditional right, subject to the condition of depositing certain percentage and/or furnishing of security in the form of surety bond or bank guarantee, as the case may be, of the disputed amount of liability fastened by the Original Adjudicating Authority/ Assessing Officer.','','','2019-08-13 08:52:39.075227','2019-08-13 08:53:43.145113',0,'1._gst.png',1),(96,'GST authorities granted time to file affidavit where Tran-III was not filed by assessee on time due to technical error','GST: Where assessee filed writ petition challenging decision taken by GST Council in meeting held on 22-12-2018 and contended that by above decision Form GST TRAN-3 could not be filed within period of limitation in view of technical glitches, GST Authorities were granted time to take instructions and file affidavit in this regard','','','2019-08-13 08:54:07.903432','2019-08-13 08:54:57.967635',0,'8._gst.jpg',1),(97,'Tools supplied by OEM to Component manufacturer for free shall not be added to value of component','GST : Cost of tool/s supplied by original equipment manufacturer (OEM) on free of cost (FOC) basis to applicant component manufacturer on returnable basis did not constitute a supply as there was no consideration and in such cases, value of goods provided on FOC basis would not be added to value of supply of components\n\n The applicant company was involved in the manufacture and sale of plastic moulds, press tools, jigs/fixtures/gauges, injection moulded parts and design services, as per specific orders & requirements of their customers. The injection moulded parts (tools), as per specific order from customer, were manufactured using plastic granules as raw material and using in-house injection moulding machines. The applicant submitted that the tool was either manufactured by them or supplied by the customers free of cost, for production of \'parts\', on returnable basis.\n\n The applicant further submitted that the injection moulds (tools) supplied by the customers at free of cost basis, for the manufacture of parts, on returnable basis were classified under capital goods. The mould (tool) had specific life and could produce only certain volume of total production. Every part produced had incurred a portion of the mould (Tool) cost that appeared as transaction value, if the tool was provided by the applicant. In the instant case the customer was supplying the tool on free of cost basis and hence the applicant was not charging any portion of the cost of the tool to the customer.\n\n The applicant sought advance ruling for the clarification regarding applicability of tool amortisation cost (transaction value) in GST Regime on capital goods received freely on returnable basis from the recipients (Customer) for parts production and supply. This reference particularly where the principal manufacturer provided moulds, dies, jigs and fixtures or tools to the supplier for use in manufacturing process.\n\n The CBIC in its Circular No. 47/21/2018-GST dated 8-6-2018 has clarified that Moulds and dies (Tools) owned by OEM that are provided to a component manufacturer on FOC basis do not constitute a supply as there is no consideration and in such cases, the value of goods provided on FOC basis shall not be added to the value of supply of components. However, in case the contractual obligation is cast upon the component manufacturer to provide moulds/dies but the same have been provided by the OEM on FOC basis, then the amortized cost of the moulds/dies is required to be added to the value of the components supplied.\n\n Thus, Cost of tool/s supplied by original equipment manufacturer (OEM) on free of cost (FOC) basis to applicant is not required to be added to the value of the parts supplied by the applicant and hence the same value is not liable for GST.\n\nread more\ntaxmann.com','','','2019-08-13 08:55:12.197982','2019-08-13 08:56:20.432056',0,'ome.png',1),(98,'Supply of pump sets with installation, electrification & energization is a composite supply & not works contract','GST : In case of applicant engaged in manufacture and supply of submersible pump sets and accessories along with installation, electrification and energisation; applicants supply of submersible pump sets and installation, electrification and energisation of same to Government entities is composite supply wherein principal supply is that of supply of such goods i.e. submersible pumps and applicable GST rate on composite supply would be rate of GST applicable to principal supply i.e submersible pump sets','','','2019-08-13 08:56:31.569446','2019-08-13 08:57:39.698511',0,'pump.jpg',1),(99,'GST payable on transaction value of supply of partially completed flats where customers identified post 01.07.2017','GST : Where, applicant was engaged in construction and sale of residential apartments, seeks advance ruling on applicability of GST on partially completed flats, in respect of partially completed flats having identified customers before GST regime, the applicant is liable to pay service tax under the Finance Act, 1994 proportionate to the services provided up to 30-6-2017 and from 1-7-2017 onwards, liable to pay GST proportionate to the services provided effective from 1-7-2017, in terms of section 142(11)(b) of the CGST Act, 2017; in respect of partially completed flats, where customers are identified after implementation of GST, the applicant is liable to pay GST on the transaction value of supply and; in respect of partially completed flats, where no customers are identified the applicant is not liable to GST as no supply is involved. However, if the supply is made prior to the issuance of completion certificate then GST is liable to be paid on the transaction value of supply','','','2019-08-13 08:57:51.643725','2019-08-13 08:58:56.304502',0,'gst_10.jpg',1),(100,'GST leviable on construction work executed under Joint Development Agreement on land owners portion of land','GST : Where applicant is engaged in construction and sale of residential apartments under joint development agreements (agreement between land owner and developer) and has executed projects under JDA with land owners for an agreed ratio of built-up area, applicant is liable to pay GST towards work executed under Joint Development Agreement on land owner\'s portion, on value to be arrived at in terms of para 2 of Notification No. 11/2017-Central Tax (Rate), dated 28-6-2017 at time of transfer of possession of land owners\' portion of flats','','','2019-08-13 08:59:08.497120','2019-08-13 09:00:02.123611',0,'c.jpg',1),(101,'Printing carried on the manufactured paper is not liable to excise duty','GST/EXCISE/ST/VAT: Where assessee received base paper in roll form from principal and carried out printing activities thereon and claimed that printed paper was classifiable under Heading No. 4911 99 90 and it was not liable to pay duty on its clearance; whereas Adjudicating Authority held that printed paper was classifiable under Heading No. 4811 90 99 and demanded duty from assessee, even if printed paper was classifiable under Heading No. 4811 90 99 or under Heading No. 4911 99 90, assessee was not liable to pay duty','','','2019-08-13 09:00:14.996830','2019-08-13 09:01:07.344190',0,'printing.jpg',1),(102,'All Industry Rates (AIRs) not required for calculation of Brand Rate of duty drawback in GST regime','On August 8, 2019 vide Circular 24/2019-Customs, CBIC has clarified that applicability of All Industry Rates (AIRs) for calculation of Brand Rate of duty drawback is no longer required for exports made in GST regime. For duty rebates under Duty drawback scheme in post-GST era, which are not refunded can be claimed by the exporter on actual basis as per rules specified for the Duty drawback scheme.','','','2019-08-13 09:01:22.143657','2019-08-13 09:02:01.315472',0,'',1),(103,'Refund for Penultimate Sale','If an exporter purchases any goods from a registered supplier with the intention of exporting the same, then the transaction between the registered supplier and the exporter would be called as Penultimate Sale.','','','2019-08-13 09:02:17.894522','2019-08-13 09:03:13.315801',0,'refund.jpg',1),(104,'HC directed assessee\'s banker to pay assessees admitted interest liability out of balance available in its account','GST: Where Competent Authority issued on assessee a notice for payment of a certain amount as interest under section 50 and also vide communication dated 21-5-2019 under section 79 called upon assessee\'s banker to make payment in pursuance of aforesaid demand, assessee\'s banker was directed to make payment of assessee\'s admitted interest liability out of balance available in its account and on such payment impugned communication will stand set aside','','','2019-08-13 09:03:26.609307','2019-08-13 09:04:25.717599',0,'intrest.jpg',1),(105,'HC directed revenue authorities to permit the assessee\'s to download \'C\' forms post GST-implementation','GST/Excise/ST/VAT: Where assessee was making inter-State purchases of High Speed Diesel Oil on concessional rate of tax at 2 per cent against \'C\' Forms and after introduction of GST regime revenue authorities informed assessee that with effect from 1-7-2017 it was not entitled to make purchase of High Speed Diesel Oil from other States on concessional rate of tax and, therefore, department\'s site had been blocked to deny access to assessee from downloading \'C\' Forms, revenue authorities were directed to take necessary action to permit assessee to download \'C\' Forms','','','2019-08-13 09:04:46.084399','2019-08-13 09:07:11.082250',0,'S.jpg',1),(106,'No coercive action to recover tax as assessee already deposited 12.5% of disputed tax amount; SLP dismissed','GST/EXCISE/ST/VAT: Where during pendency of appellate proceedings, assessee had already deposited 12.5 per cent of disputed tax amount for purpose of maintaining an appeal and, thus, High Court restrained revenue authorities from taking coercive measures for collection of balance disputed tax in terms of assessment order, SLP filed against order passed by High Court was to be dismissed','','','2019-08-22 07:08:37.164318','2019-08-22 07:22:29.691049',0,'1._gst_ZFgdmxm.png',1),(107,'HC directed AAAR to consider submissions made by the applicant and issue its order accordingly','GST : Where AAAR\'s rejected assessee\'s claim of ITC on purchase of vans used in cash carrying business without dealing with assessee\'s primary submission that \'money\' carried in cash form would be treated as \'goods\'','','','2019-08-22 07:22:32.800480','2019-08-22 07:25:07.636995',0,'8._gst_S184K1N.jpg',1),(108,'Contributions received from members for meeting administrative expenses are supply of services under GST','GST : Where applicant Rotary Club collects fees from their members in order to facilitate their meetings and for administrative purposes, contributions from members in Administration Account, recovered for expending same for weekly and other meetings and other petty administrative expenses incurred including expenses for location and light refreshments, amounts to or results in a supply, within meaning of supply and will be classified as supply of services for which applicant is liable to pay GST','','','2019-08-22 07:25:46.040234','2019-08-22 07:27:17.932073',0,'9._gst.jpg',1),(109,'Matter to be reconsidered by AAAR where it introduced \'New grounds\' without notifying assessee about the same','GST: AAAR\'s holding that conversion of coal into electricity is manufacturing liable to GST, being based on totally new grounds and without hearing assessee, was to be remanded\n\nGST: Statute has provided for no further appeal against decision of AAAR; validity of AAAR\'s decision is to be examined by applying principles of judicial review','','','2019-08-22 07:27:19.648550','2019-08-22 07:29:01.464156',0,'108027.png',1),(110,'ITC inadmissible if motor vehicle purchased to provide Rent-a-Cab service','In a recent AAR-West Bengal Ruling in the case of Mohana Ghosh, Inre [2019] 106 taxmann.com 108 suo motu amended by AAR on 25-6-2019 reported in 106 taxmann.com 380, the issue of admissibility or otherwise of the input tax credit (ITC) of GST paid on inward supply/purchase of motor vehicle for supply of rent-a-cab/Renting/Leasing/Hiring service, has been considered and analysed.','','','2019-08-22 07:29:02.481245','2019-08-22 07:31:02.462421',0,'108010_1.jpg',1),(111,'Merger and Acquisition - GST Perspective','In todays era, business combinations are very frequent and can create different types of synergies based on the objective of such combinations.','','','2019-08-22 07:31:07.037712','2019-08-22 07:32:35.717275',0,'108009.jpg',1),(112,'HC orders release of detained goods & vehicle of the assessee on furnishing bank guarantee for tax & penalty','GST: Where Competent Authority had detained goods of assessee under transport and issued a notice under section 129(3) demanding tax and penalty, said authority was directed to release goods upon assessee furnishing bank guarantee for tax and penalty amount demanded in notice','','','2019-08-22 07:33:00.946487','2019-08-22 07:34:00.258613',0,'108098.jpg',1),(113,'Land given on lease could not be attached to recover tax dues of the company','GST/EXCISE/ST/VAT : Where assessee-company was legal owner of a certain land and it had given on lease said land to a Company \'R\' and two directors of assessee-company were also directors in company \'R\' and company \'R\' had defaulted in payment of tax under Gujarat VAT Act, land of assessee-company could not have been attached for purpose of recovering dues payable by company \'R\'','','','2019-08-22 07:34:17.582631','2019-08-22 07:35:09.027398',0,'108029.jpg',1),(114,'Agricultural Activities - GST Perspective','Agriculture is the science and art of cultivating plants and livestock. A farmer(also called an agriculturist) is a person engaged in agriculture, raising living organisms for food or raw materials. Agriculture is the main source of livelihood of rural people of our country and major work forces are engaged in agricultural sectors.','','','2019-08-22 07:35:11.220385','2019-08-22 07:36:27.960456',0,'108032.jpg',1),(115,'All about Sabka Vishwas (Legacy Dispute Resolution) Scheme, 2019','The Finance (No. 2) Act, 2019 introduced a new scheme \'Sabka Viswas Legacy Dispute Resolution Scheme, 2019\' in order to resolve the pending litigations in relation to excise and service tax matters.','','','2019-08-22 07:36:30.128221','2019-08-22 07:37:34.736102',0,'9._gst_p0Gxlgo.jpg',1),(116,'Narcotic Chewing Tablet is a chemical product, taxed @ 18% GST','GST : Appropriate classification of Nicotine Polacriliex Lozenge (NCT) being manufactured by applicant pharmaceutical company contains nicotine which is not an edible/ food preparation. Therefore, it is rightly classifiable under heading 3824. Accordingly product NCT is covered under Serial number 97 of Schedule III to Notification No. 01/2017-Central Tax (Rate) dated 28-6-2017 and attracts GST at rate of 18 per cent (9 per cent CGST, 9 per cent SGST)','','','2019-08-22 07:39:27.024047','2019-08-22 07:46:58.580062',0,'108233.jpg',1),(117,'Supply of frozen seafood in packages with Co. name & contact details to institutional customers is taxable under GST','GST : Where applicant, which is registered brand name holder is engaged in processing and sale of frozen seafood in India as well as export out of India, it is held that supply of frozen seafood in packages to institutional customers contain name of company and contract details for customers which are statutory requirements and presence of company name is sufficient to ensure that product procured belongs to \'brand guardian\' and it cannot be considered as not bearing a brand name and, therefore, same is not eligible for exemption (NIL rate) under Notification No. 2/2017 (Central Tax Rate/Integrated Tax Rate/State Tax Rate), dated 28-6-2017','','','2019-08-22 07:47:20.902637','2019-08-22 07:48:10.321728',0,'108235.jpg',1),(118,'Propellers, SS rods, Gun metal bearing, etc., used as parts of fishing vessels are taxable @ 5% GST','GST : Propeller, Shaft/SS rod, Gun metal bush/bearing, Stuffing box, Brass Tube/SS Tube, Rudder Shaft and Blade, Sea Cork/Water Stainer, GM Gate Valve, MS Pipe, Propeller Nut/GM Nut, Coupling, SS Rods & Square, SS Flat, GM Gland and Ring and MS Plate used as parts of fishing/floating vessels come under Heading No. 8902 and are taxable at rate of 5 per cent (2.5 per cent CGST + 2.5 per cent SGST) under Sl. No. 252 of First Schedule of Notification No. 1/2017-Central Tax (Rate), dated 28-6-2017','','','2019-08-22 07:48:25.233693','2019-08-22 07:49:24.501210',0,'108236.jpg',1),(119,'Separate GST registrations allowable to multiple companies functioning from same address','GST : Where applicant is engaged in business of sub-leasing of office spaces as \'co-working spaces\' to their clients and in \'co-working space model\' it offers dedicated distinct and identifiable space, tables and chair to each client working there and each client company is working as separate and identifiable office within main office, separate GST registration can be allowed to multiple companies functioning in a \'co-working space\' and which provide services alone. Such companies shall upload rental agreement with landlord and lessee. If there is any sub-lease, then rental agreement between lessee and sub-lessee should also be uploaded as proof of address of principal place of business of respective suit or desk number assigned to them','','','2019-08-22 07:50:32.112772','2019-08-22 07:53:44.718965',0,'108234.jpg',1),(120,'Period for furnishing bank guarantee under GST extended due to attachment of bank account of assessee','GST : Where High Court vide order dated 8-2-2019 had directed assessee to furnish bank guarantee for a sum of Rs. 55 lakhs within a period of one month and also directed it to pay balance amount in monthly instalments and assessee filed application before High Court seeking extention of time period for furnishing bank guarantee, since assessee had already paid first three instalments, period for furnishing bank guarantee deserved to be extended','','','2019-08-22 07:54:01.056020','2019-08-22 07:54:38.233486',0,'8._gst_LRG972a.jpg',1),(121,'High time for the Government to resolve pre-GST era litigations','There has been a lot of debate and discussion with regard to the alarming scale of pending litigations in the field of indirect taxes relating to the Pre-GST era. Lately, the impact of such disturbing scale of pending litigations has driven the Finance Ministry to design an amnesty scheme, namely, Legacy Dispute Resolution Scheme in order to get rid of such menacing phenomena.','','','2019-08-22 07:54:52.066250','2019-08-22 07:55:34.413517',0,'BNSNews501082019_D9L9dhf.png',1),(122,'Sale of goods at International Airport Departure terminal by duty free shops is to be treated as \'export of goods\'','GST: Where one \'R\' had been operating duty free shops (DFS) at Lucknow Airport, sale/supply of goods at International Airport departure terminals by DFS would amount to export of goods\n\nGST: Where one \'R\' had been operating duty free shops at Lucknow Airport, any accumulated unutilized input tax credit would be refundable to \'R\'','','','2019-08-22 07:56:06.692319','2019-08-22 07:56:23.314894',0,'',1),(123,'Engines manufactured for use in railways denied benefit of 5% GST by AAR','Cummins India Ltd., In re [2019] 103 taxmann.com 126/73 GST 517 (AAR - Maharashtra). In this case the applicant, has raised the undermentioned question before the Hon\'ble AAR, for determination, viz.,','','','2019-08-22 07:56:25.605117','2019-08-22 07:58:17.771245',0,'108159_1.jpg',1),(124,'The quagmire in tax laws','The staggering stakes involved in tax disputes appear to have transformed the working relationship between Revenue and India Inc. Any process, whether worded with simplicity or complexity in law, needs to be implemented with fair play and empathy by the Revenue. Simultaneously, an assesssee is required to keep a promise or adhere to time lines set for clearing its tax dues before a Revenue officer.','','','2019-08-22 07:58:33.216526','2019-08-22 08:00:42.637391',0,'108239.jpg',1),(125,'E-way bill cannot be generated after November 21, 2019, if return for 2 consecutive tax periods is not filed','On August 20, 2019 vide Notification No. 36/2019-Central Tax, CBIC has extended the date from August 21, 2019 to November 21, 2019 from which no person (including a consignor, consignee, transporter, an e-commerce operator or a courier agency) shall be allowed to generate an e-way bill, if he has not furnished the returns for two consecutive tax periods.','','','2019-08-22 08:01:05.722875','2019-08-22 08:01:59.510184',0,'BNSNews121082019.jpg',1),(126,'Adjudicating Authority can\'t reclassify energy drinks in heading 22021090 after classifying it in heading 22029090','GST/EXCISE/ST/VAT: Where assessee imported \'Power Energy Drinks\' and classified same under Heading No. 2202 10 10 and thereafter on proposal of Adjudicating Authority reclassified said product under Heading No. 2202 90 90 and later on Adjudicating Authority took exception to such classification and passed an order holding that product in question was classifiable under Heading No. 2202 10 90, impugned order was without jurisdiction','','','2019-08-22 08:02:16.907800','2019-08-22 08:02:59.886027',0,'108100.jpg',1),(127,'AAAR could not condone the delay for filing an appeal beyond 30 days, hence appeal dismissed, being time barred','CGST : Appellate Authority being a creature of statute is empowered to condone a delay of only a period of 30 days after expiry of initial period for filing appeal, and to hold that Appellate Authority could entertain appeal beyond extended period would render phrase \'not exceeding thirty days\' wholly otiose and no principle of interpretation would justify such a result','','','2019-08-22 08:03:15.113238','2019-08-22 08:03:58.042943',0,'108100_qtlmgAx.jpg',1),(128,'Power Bank is classified as an Accumulator taxable @ 18% having Lithium-ion battery, otherwise @ 28% GST','GST : Where appellant Xiaomi is trading \'Power Bank\' whose principal function is to store electric energy and supply when required, power bank traded by appellant is not static convertor but is classifiable as an accumulator under Chapter Heading 8507\n\n(Xiaomi Technology India (P.) Ltd., In re [2019] 102 taxmann.com 28 (AAR - Karnataka) affirmed.)','','','2019-08-22 08:04:10.953650','2019-08-22 08:05:03.557354',0,'108259.jpg',1),(129,'Assessee ordered to be released on bail for offence committed under GST on execution of personal bond with one surety','GST: Where assessee was in jail since 18-1-2019 for an offence punishable under section 132(1)(b), he was ordered to be released on regular bail on executing a personal bond of Rs. 10,000 with one surety of like amount','','','2019-08-22 08:05:20.561990','2019-08-22 08:06:20.074604',0,'1._gst_8csDuoE.png',1),(130,'Availability of ITC for expenses incurred towards promotional schemes','Sanofi India Limited in India is engaged in business of sale of pharmaceutical goods and services through group entities. Sanofi has its head office in Mumbai and manufacturing unit at Goa and Ankleshwar. Sanofi also gets its products manufactured through Third party manufacturers who manufacture goods on Contract manufacturing basis.','','','2019-08-22 08:06:22.103330','2019-08-22 08:07:40.952555',0,'gst_return_vwywyyZ.jpg',1),(131,'CBIC extended the due date of filing GSTR-3B for July, 2019','On August 21, 2019, vide Notification No.-37/2019- Central Tax, CBIC has extended the due date of filing monthly return in Form GSTR-3B for the month of July, 2019 to August 22, 2019. However, in specified flood affected districts and in the State of Jammu & Kashmir the due date for filing Form GSTR-3B for July, 2019 has been extended to September 20, 2019.','','','2019-08-22 08:08:17.583149','2019-08-22 08:08:56.664899',0,'8._gst_O6uWYfL.jpg',1),(132,'Central Govt. notifies the GSTAT (Appointment and Conditions of Service of President and Members) Rules, 2019','Vide Notification having G.S.R. 584 (E), dated August 21, 2019, the Central Govt. has notified the Goods and Services Tax Appellate Tribunal (Appointment and Conditions of Service of President and Members) Rules, 2019. These rules shall come into force on the date of their publication in the Official Gazette.','','','2019-08-27 06:01:50.186414','2019-08-27 06:04:02.045714',0,'9._gst_hJUsNxe.jpg',1),(133,'Royalty paid to obtain license for mining lease from govt. for exploration of natural resources is taxed @ 18% GST','GST : Where applicant, engaged in business of mining of Soapstone and Dolomite, entered into a lease transfer agreement for obtaining mining lease from Government for exploration of natural resources like oil, hydrocarbons, iron ore, manganese etc., against consideration in form of annual license fee, lease charges, royalty, etc. to Government, activity undertaken by applicant is classifiable under heading 997337 taxable at rate of 18 per cent under entry No. 17(viii) of Notification No. 11/2017-Central Tax (Rate) dated 28-6-2017\n\n(Aravali Polyart (P.) Ltd., In re [2019] 103 taxmann.com 382 (AAR - RAJASTHAN) - Upheld)','','','2019-08-27 06:04:31.521825','2019-08-27 06:09:24.214571',0,'108373.jpg',1),(134,'Key announcements made by the FM in the press conference','In an unprecedented move, the Finance Minister has held a press conference on Friday, August 23, 2019 to announce certain measures Govt. will be taking to give a boost to the securities market and economy. The key announcement made by the Finance Minister are discussed in this article.','','','2019-08-27 06:10:06.274840','2019-08-27 06:11:03.727884',0,'News000123082019.jpg',1),(135,'Competent Authority to take possible steps after considering documents submitted by assessee for amendment to Tran-1','GST : Where assessee filed writ petition seeking directions to Competent Authority to permit it to amend Form GST TRAN-1 and to claim eligible credit towards central tax, Competent Authority was directed to do everything needful and complete entire exercise including refund of amount to assessee','','','2019-08-27 06:11:17.988811','2019-08-27 06:11:51.365633',0,'1._gst_8BSj0FP.png',1),(136,'Goods such as \'Plant Leaf Extract\' are classified under Heading 1302 19 90','GST/EXCISE/ST/VAT: Where assessee had imported certain goods and declared same as \'Plant Leaf Extract\' classifiable under Heading No. 1302 19 90, since there was no presence of oxymatrine in impugned goods, goods were rightly classifiable under Heading No. 1302 19 90','','','2019-08-27 06:12:06.426858','2019-08-27 06:12:56.463567',0,'108032_6YVfsKG.jpg',1),(137,'Tax liability not to be imposed where transitional credit wrongly reflected in electronic ledger has not been availed','GST : Where assessee was not entitled to transitional credit, at best, claim could be rejected but such rejection of claim for transitional credit does not bestow any statutory jurisdiction upon Assessing Authority to correspondingly create a tax liability especially when neither any such outstanding liability exists nor such credit has been put to use\n\n Provisions underlying section 73 are self eloquent and it is only if such availment is for reducing a tax liability that it vests jurisdiction in Assessing Authority to recover such tax together with levy of interest and penalty under section 50 but until such time that statutory authority is able to demonstrate that any tax was recoverable from assessee, a reflection in electronic credit ledger cannot be treated as an \'availment\'.','','','2019-08-27 06:13:34.671271','2019-08-27 06:14:41.584584',0,'108377.jpg',1),(138,'Supply, design, testing, etc., of solar energy based water pumping systems are both supply of goods & services in GST','GST : Activities of supply, design, installation, commissioning and testing of solar energy based water pumping systems, whose time of supply falls after 31-12-2018, are both supply of Goods and supply of Services in terms of entry No. 234 ibid, read with entry No. 38 ibid, with rate of GST as prescribed under these entries\n\n(Kailash Chandra, In re [2019] 102 taxmann.com 210 (AAR- RAJASTHAN) - Modified)','','','2019-08-27 06:14:56.517134','2019-08-27 06:15:53.381230',0,'108406.jpg',1),(139,'Persons Registered in a particular State cant claim credit of GST paid on hotel services availed in other State','CGST : In GST regime, SGST and CGST charged for services provided and availed in a State would be eligible for ITC within that particular State where such services were provided and consumed\n\n Where applicant-company, registered in Rajasthan State for GST law, procures services of short term accommodation (i.e., Hotel) in Haryana and said Hotel charges CGST and SGST, ITC of the Central Tax charged from appellant in Haryana is not available to them as in this case both location of supplier and place of supply of services are in the State of Haryana.\n\n(IMF Cognitive Technology (P.) Ltd., In re [2019] 102 taxmann.com 211 (AAR - Rajasthan) affirmed.)','','','2019-08-27 06:16:06.263295','2019-08-27 06:17:09.397040',0,'108412.jpg',1),(140,'Leasing activities - GST Perspective','In this era when daily new developments are taking place, we can see a trend among people of shifting more towards lease transactions. Further, opening of new platforms like Zoomcar, volecars, etc., has made car leasing option trendier. Fast-rising home prices and higher mortgage rates have made home renting cheaper than buying & owning one.','','','2019-08-27 06:17:22.383928','2019-08-27 06:18:21.695336',0,'108371.jpg',1),(141,'HC directed Competent Authority to release detained goods & vehicle on furnishing of simple bond or bank guarantee','GST : Where Competent Authority had detained goods of assessee as well as vehicle on plea that in original E-way Bill place of delivery was not correctly shown and in revised E-way bill value of goods was not correctly shown, said authority was directed to release goods on assessee executing a simple bond, if it was found that assessee had paid tax in accordance with value of goods shown in original E-way Bill','','','2019-08-27 06:18:35.176314','2019-08-27 06:20:39.957814',0,'108165.jpg',1),(142,'Due date for filing of GST Annual Return (GSTR-9/9A) & GST Audit (GSTR-9C) extended to November 30, 2019','On August 26, 2019 vide Order No. 7/2019-Central Tax, CBIC has extended the due date for filing of GST Annual Return and GST Audit from August 31, 2019 to November 30, 2019 for the period July, 2017 to March, 2018.','','','2019-08-27 06:20:56.944855','2019-08-27 06:22:04.688758',0,'gst_return_2PMFwiK.jpg',1),(143,'Payment of additional liability in annual return by ITC','The 1st of July 2019 marked the completion of two years of introduction of Goods and Services Tax (GST). The Government must be commended for its proactive approach in resolving issues faced by the trade. However, one issue which is plaguing the trade at large is the mandatory requirement for payment of any additional liability, declared in GST annual form, by cash only.','','','2019-08-28 05:43:01.688461','2019-08-28 06:12:37.294743',0,'107229.jpg',1),(144,'Mobilization advance given for works contract before GST implementation is leviable to GST','GST : Mobilization advance for works contract is meant specifically for inducing contractor to spend for provisioning works contract service, hence GST is leviable thereon accordingly\n\nFacts\n\n Applicant has entered into a contract with Kolkata Metro Rail Corporation ( KMRCL) for \'design, supply, installation, testing and commissioning\' of power supply and distribution system, third rail system and SCADA system for entire line and depot of Kolkata East-West Metro Rail Project. lt includes supply of equipment, training of personnel etc. He has been awarded onshore scope of work for contract under an open consortium arrangement with offshore contractor Siemens AG.\n\n According to Contract, applicant received mobilisation advance, which was 10 per cent of original contract value. The lump-sum mobilisation amount so received is recoverable as adjustment towards payment due for tax invoices that applicant raises on attaining contract progress milestones. Applicant\'s question relates to GST implication on lump-sum so received before implementation of GST and its recovery by KMRCL against applicant\'s sales invoices issued post introduction of GST. More specifically, applicant wants to know whether GST shall be charged on gross amount of invoice or net amount after adjusting lump-sum amount outstanding as on 30-6-2017.\n\nHeld\n\n Mobilisation advance is meant specifically for inducing the contractor to spend for provisioning the works contract service. The contract provides a mechanism in the form of a bank guarantee that ensures that the advance is not diverted or misappropriated. Its application as payment for inducing the supply is, therefore, direct and unambiguous. It is, therefore, \'consideration,\' whether or not in the form of a deposit, for the supply of the works contract service. The Contract makes it amply clear that the entire amount is applied as consideration for provisioning works contract service.\n\n The Contract is to be valued as provided under section 15(1), which does not restrict in any way the scope of time of supply, as provided under section 13(2) of the GST Act. Moreover, \'consideration\' under the GST Act has a wider scope and includes deposits if applied as consideration. ln that context, whether the mobilisation advance is earnest money or not is of little relevance.\n\n Thus, the applicant is deemed to have supplied works contract service to KMRCL on 1-7-2017 to the extent covered by the lump-sum that stood credited to its account on that date as mobilisation advance and GST is leviable thereon accordingly. The value of supply of works contract service in subsequent invoices as and when raised should, therefore, be reduced to extent of advance adjusted in such invoices. The GST should, therefore, be charged on net amount that remains after such adjustment.','','','2019-08-28 06:13:15.362011','2019-08-28 06:14:08.051072',0,'108460.jpg',1),(145,'Loading or unloading services w.r.t. imported cargo of yellow peas at port of entry are taxable under GST','GST: Where applicant supplied service of loading, unloading, etc., after cargo of yellow peas, imported from a foreign land, reached port of entry, such imported yellow peas were not \'agricultural produce\' and services by way of handing of it was not eligible for exemption under Sl No. 54(e) of Notification No. 12/2017 - Central Tax (Rate) dated 28-6-2017 (corresponding State Notification No. 1136 - FT dated 28-6-2017), as amended from time\n\n The applicant was acting as a stevedore and was handling imported raw whole yellow peas. It sought a ruling on whether such imported yellow peas were \'agricultural produce\' and services by way of handing of it was eligible for exemption under Sl. no. 54(e) of Notification No. 12/2017 - Central Tax (Rate) dated 28-6-2017 (corresponding State Notification No. 1136 - FT dated 28-6-2017), as amended from time to time.\n\n Circular no. 16/16/2017-GST dated 15-11-2017 of CBIC clarifies that the process of de-dusking or splitting of pulses is usually not carried out by farmers or at the farm level but by the pulse millers and, therefore, such products are not to be considered \'agricultural produce\'. The emphasis, therefore, is on the processes and services that are applied till the goods are at the farmer\'s hand. As soon as they leave the farmer\'s hand and the primary market, the services rendered thereafter are not to be considered related to cultivation of the plant and classifiable under SAC 9986.\n\n The applicant renders the service of loading, unloading etc. after the cargo of yellow peas, imported from a foreign land, reaches the port of entry. The produce has been procured from the farmers in the foreign land and exported to India. Clearly, it is, whether processed in a mill, no longer in the domain of the primary market or at the farmer\'s hand. Exemption under Sl No. 54(e) of the Exemption Notification, therefore, is not applicable to the applicant\'s services.\n\nread more','','','2019-08-28 06:15:17.969111','2019-08-28 06:16:04.999055',0,'108459.jpg',1),(146,'Rectification facility has been extended to match invoices with shipping bills filed by the Exporters up-to 31.07.2019','On August 27, 2017 vide Circular No. 26/2019-Customs, CBIC has extended the rectification facility in respect SB005 error indicating invoice mismatches in shipping bills and GST returns for Shipping Bills filed up to July 31, 2019.','','','2019-08-28 06:16:17.161159','2019-08-28 06:17:09.549500',0,'BNSNews427082019.jpg',1),(147,'No ITC on inward supplies for in-house hospital providing medical facilities to employees','GST : Where applicant engaged in supply of port services is maintaining an in-house hospital within its port premises for providing health and medical cover exclusively to its employees and pensioners, inward supply of goods and services are used by employees and dependents of applicant and, hence, are for personal consumption and applicant is ineligible to take input tax credit on inward supply of medical, diagnostic equipment, apparatus, instruments, consumables, disposables, spares and repairing services for these are used to provide health facilities to its employees in its hospital','','','2019-08-28 06:17:23.138563','2019-08-28 06:18:00.911119',0,'108240.jpg',1),(148,'CBIC clarifies the importance & advantages of Sabka Vishwas (Legacy Dispute Resolution) Scheme, 2019','On August 27, 2019 vide Circular No. 1071/4/2019-Central Excise, CBIC has clarified the importance and benefits of Sabka Vishwas (Legacy Dispute Resolution) Scheme, 2019.','','','2019-08-28 06:18:13.906632','2019-08-28 06:18:59.633531',0,'BNSNews527082019.jpg',1),(149,'Supply of printing services along with ink and base material is a composite supply under GST','GST : Where applicant, engaged in business of printing of trade advertisement material, prints content provided by recipient on base of polyvinyl chloride cloth, paper, etc., and provides printing ink and base material, applicant\'s supply is a composite contract, a transaction involving both services and transfer of property in goods, and two are inseparable in execution of contract. The goods supplied having no other use other than displaying printed matter, is ancillary to the principal supply of printing','','','2019-08-28 06:19:12.156224','2019-08-28 06:21:11.504758',0,'108463_1.jpg',1),(150,'AAAR upheld AARs ruling that registration required for taxable & exempt supplies if turnover exceeds threshold limit','GST : Exemption provided at Sl.No. 1 of Notification No. 12/2017-C.T.(Rate) dated 28-6-2017 exempts payment of GST only in respect of services provided by way of \'Charitable activities\' relating to \'Preservation of environment including watershed, forests and wildlife\' and construction of exemption is not to provide exemption to all activities undertaken by an entity registered under section 12A of the Income tax Act, which is involved in activities relating to \'Preservation of environment\'\n\n Activities undertaken by appellant a society under Marine Products Export Development Authority, are of diverse nature ranging from sensitizing farmers/entrepreneurs; training students/academia; undertaking testing for pathogens, quality of farms; supply of fish seeds; artemia Cyst(processed) for fish feed; etc. Hence, appellant as an entity in entirety is not exempted from payment of GST or in other words, exemption under Sl. No. 1 of Notification No. 12/2017-C.T.(Rate) dated 28-6-2017 is not applicable to all supplies made by appellant and therefore appellant is required to get registered under GST Laws subject to them making taxable supplies and other conditions spelt under section 23.\n\n(Rajiv Gandhi Centre For Aquaculture, In re [2019] 104 taxmann.com 381 (AAR - TAMILNADU) - Upheld).','','','2019-08-28 06:21:24.534214','2019-08-28 06:22:18.851112',0,'108234_0azMinj.jpg',1),(151,'Cattle feed in cake form manufactured by the assessee is exempt from GST','GST : Product \'cattle feed in cake form\' manufactured by applicant was classifiable under Chapter Heading 23099010 and stands exempted as per Sl. No. 102 of Notification No. 2/2017-Central Tax (Rate), dated 28-6-2017 as amended and Sl. No. 102 of Notification No. II(2)/CTR/532(d-5)/2017, dated 29-6-2017 as amended and in case of interstate supplies vide Sl. No. 102 of Notification No. 2/2017-Integrated tax (Rate), dated 28-6-2017 as amended\n\n The applicant was engaged in the manufacture of \'cattle feed in cake form\'. It was effecting sales of cattle feed (cakeform) both locally as well as by way of inter-state sale. The applicant contended that right from the inception under the sales tax enactment, cattle feed in cake form manufactured by them were eligible for exemption under the TNGST Act 1959, under the TNVAT Act, 2006. It submitted that since the product manufactured by them could be used only as cattle feed meant for animals there could not be any liability by way of tax under GST Act. In view of the above facts the applicant requested to issue an advance ruling with regard to the classification of their product \'cattle feed in cake form\'.\n\n The product \'cattle feed in cake form\' manufactured by the applicant is classifiable under Chapter Heading 23099010 and stands exempted as per Sl. No. 102 of Notification No. 2/2017-Central Tax (Rate), dated 28-6-2017 as amended and Sl. No. 102 of Notification No. II(2)/CTR/532(d-5)/2017, dated 29-6-2017 as amended and in case of interstate supplies vide Sl. No. 102 of Notification No. 2/2017-Integrated Tax (Rate), dated 28-6-2017 as amended.','','','2019-08-28 06:22:36.300358','2019-08-28 06:23:35.660557',0,'108464.jpg',1),(152,'Circular issued on sanction of pending refunds due to mismatches between GSTR-1 & GSTR-3B for F.Y. 2018-19','On August 27, 2019 vide Circular No. 25/2019-Customs, CBIC has extended the benefit of pending refund claims of exporters arising due mismatches between GSTR-1 and GSTR-3B for the shipping bills filed during the period April, 2018 to March, 2019. Certificate from a Chartered Accountant is required to be furnished by October 30, 2019 evidencing that no discrepancy between amount refunded and IGST paid exists.','','','2019-08-28 06:23:37.582738','2019-08-28 06:24:59.132568',0,'BNSNews627082019.jpg',1),(153,'Services of evacuation & disposal of settled ash for local authority is exempt from GST','GST : Where applicant provided service to Purba Medinipur Zila Parishad (PMZP) to undertake evacuation and disposal of settled ash from ash ponds of Kolaghat Thermal Power Station (KTPS) to ensure uninterrupted power generation, protection of environment and augmentation of local fund, applicant\'s supply to PMZP is a composite supply classifiable under SAC 995433 and is exempt under SI No. 3A of Notification No. 12/2017-Central Tax (Rate) dated 28-6-2017 (corresponding State Notification No. 1136-FT dated 28-6-2017), as amended from time to time','','','2019-08-28 06:25:11.596622','2019-08-28 06:25:58.298584',0,'108462.jpg',1),(154,'Manufacture and transportation of nutritious weaning food to children is composite supply, taxed @ 5% GST','GST : Supply of \'Complementary Weaning Food containing Amylase activity\' and transportation at specified destinations as per bid/agreement is a composite supply liable to GST at 5 per cent\n\n Where applicant-company are manufacturing and supplying \'complementary weaning food containing Amylase activity\' to the department of Integrated Child Development Services and they have also been transporting these food items through goods carriage vehicle owned by them, there are two supplies, one of supply of the food products and the other of supply of service of transporting the goods to the specified ICDS centers and supply of \'Complementary weaning food containing Amylase activity\' being naturally bundled with the delivery at the designated centers as specified as per the bid and agreement, this is a composite supply as per section 2(30) of the CGST/TNGST Act, 2017 and liable to GST at the rate of 5 per cent. The principal supply in this case is the supply of \'Complementary weaning food containing Amylase activity\'','','','2019-08-28 06:26:10.165993','2019-08-28 06:27:02.141114',0,'108468.png',1),(155,'Writ dismissal by Single Judge of HC with liberty to assessee to avail statutory remedy of appeal was valid','GST : Where Competent Authority had detained a new vehicle of assessee under transport and passed an order under section 129(3) imposing tax and penalty and Single Judge of High Court dismissed writ petition filed against impugned order by leaving liberty to assessee to approach Appellate Authority, liberty reserved by Single Judge for availing statutory remedy was not in any way illegal, erroneous or improper','','','2019-09-05 06:10:04.675217','2019-09-05 06:11:18.714732',0,'108214.jpg',1),(156,'Corrigendum issued to prescribe DRC-03 for payment of tax under rate notifications','On August 30, 2019 the Government of India, vide G.S.R. 611(E), G.S.R. 612(E) and G.S.R. 612(E) respectively has issued corrigendum to replace Form GST ITC-03 with Form GST DRC-03under respective rate notifications-Notification No. 03/2019- Central Tax (Rate), Notification No. 03/2019-State Tax(Rate) and Notification No. 03/2019-Union Territory Tax(Rate) dated March 29, 2019.','','','2019-09-05 06:11:29.508798','2019-09-05 06:12:25.653321',0,'BNNews531082019.jpg',1),(157,'No requirement to furnish Form ITC-04 from July, 2017 to March, 2019','On August 31, 2019 vide Notification No. 38/2019-Central Tax, CBIC has waived the requirement to furnish Form ITC-04 from July, 17 to March, 19. However, the details of challans for goods dispatched to a job worker from July, 17 to March, 19 but not received back or not supplied by job-worker from his place of business is required to be furnished in Form ITC-04 for the quarter April-June, 2019.','','','2019-09-05 06:12:37.405275','2019-09-05 06:13:31.793756',0,'108214_6A8kQP8.jpg',1),(158,'CBIC issues FAQs on Sabka Vishwas (Legacy Dispute Resolution) Scheme, 2019','CBIC has issued FAQs on Sabka Vishwas (Legacy Dispute Resolution) Scheme, 2019 which has been introduced vide Finance (No. 2) Act, 2019 to resolve and settle the pending litigations pertaining to excise and service tax matters.','','','2019-09-05 06:13:53.359768','2019-09-05 06:14:37.732041',0,'BNSNews602092019.png',1),(159,'Due date of Form GSTR-7 extended for Kashmir and specified districts','On August 31, 2019 vide Notification No. 40/2019-Central Tax, CBIC has extended the due date of Form GSTR-7 for October, 2018 to July, 2019 from August 31, 2019 to September 20, 2019 for State of Kashmir and various specified districts.','','','2019-09-05 06:14:49.778984','2019-09-05 06:16:11.070711',0,'BNSNews102092019.jpg',1),(160,'Refund of State taxes shall be disbursed by the Central Govt. from September 1, 2019','On August 31, 2019, vide Notification No. 39/2019-Central Tax, CBIC has notified that provisions granting power to Central Govt. for disbursement of refund of State taxes of the taxpayers shall come into force from September 1, 2019.','','','2019-09-05 06:16:23.800102','2019-09-05 06:20:19.974189',0,'1._gst_rLkRphc.png',1),(161,'Late fees waived for GSTR-1 & GSTR-6 for Kashmir and specified districts for month of July, 2019','On August 31, 2019 vide Notification No. 41/2019-Central Tax, CBIC has waived the late fees for furnishing monthly Form GSTR-1 and Form GSTR-6, for the month of July, 2019, if the same are furnished on or before September 20, 2019 by the registered persons in the State of Kashmir and various specified districts.','','','2019-09-05 06:21:13.528213','2019-09-05 06:21:56.599876',0,'BNSNews302092019.jpg',1),(162,'Total GST collection for August, 2019 was Rs. 98, 202 crore:PIB','GST collection in August, 2018 was Rs. 93,960 crore. The GST collection during August, 2019 had shown a growth of 4.51% over the GST collection in the same month last year.','','','2019-09-05 06:22:14.071747','2019-09-05 06:23:54.591137',0,'tax_EN21vLL.jpg',1),(163,'HC directed competent authority to release detained goods on furnishing of bank guarantee by the assessee','GST: Where Competent Authority had detained goods of assessee under transport under section 129 and determined a certain amount in this behalf, said authority was directed to release goods on assessee furnishing bank guarantee for amount determined','','','2019-09-05 06:24:07.265620','2019-09-05 06:24:32.529894',0,'',1),(164,'Notice issued to GST authorities as validity of SCN was challenged by assessee for being issued without jurisdiction','GST: Where assessee filed writ petition challenging legality and validity of show cause notice issued by Deputy Commissioner of State Tax under section 74(1) and contended that said authority had no jurisdiction to issue such show cause notice, notice was issued to GST Authorities','','','2019-09-05 06:24:36.582100','2019-09-05 06:25:30.977305',0,'108169.jpg',1),(165,'Stay granted through interim order for recovery of late fees for delay in filing Form GSTR-3B','GST : Where applicant had filed an instant writ petition to sought complete waiver of levy of late fees for late filling of Form GSTR- 3B under section 47 of CGST Act, stay was to be granted on recovery proceedings for the recovery of late fees for late filing of Form GSTR-3B\n\n The applicant had filed an instant writ petition to sought complete waiver of levy of late fees for late filling of the Form GSTR- 3B under section 47 of the CGST Act as well as the SGST Act in accordance with the second proviso to the NotificationNo.76/2018-Central Tax dated 31.12.2018 for the returns furnished upto september 2018.\n\n The writ applicant have been able to make a strong prima facie case to have an ad-interim order granting stay on recovery proceedings for the recovery of late fees for late filing of Form GSTR-3Bfor the period 1st July 2017 to 30th September 2018 for which returns are furnished between 1st July, 2017 to 21st December, 2018.','','','2019-09-05 06:25:43.116702','2019-09-05 06:26:39.261502',0,'108590.jpg',1),(166,'GST on Discounts - Whether two holes in one pocket?','Discount is probably the main attraction that fascinates the buyers but it displeases the sellers and GST Dept. When a discount is offered to a buyer, seller foregoes some probable sales revenue and Dept. foregoes tax revenue. But Dept. does not loose every time. Lets find out why? Businesses offer variety of discounts and promotional schemes to boost the revenue and to attract more customers.','','','2019-09-05 06:26:55.732134','2019-09-05 06:27:42.509180',0,'109002.jpg',1),(167,'Competent Authority to release seized goods and vehicle of assessee on deposit of full amount due by the assessee','GST : Where Competent Authority had seized goods of assessee under transport as well as vehicle and assessee had deposited an amount of Rs. 1.85 lakhs with department; whereas according to Competent Authority amount due and payable was Rs. 5.42 lakhs, Competent Authority was directed to release goods and vehicle on assessee depositing balance amount of Rs. 3.57 lakhs','','','2019-09-05 06:27:44.020565','2019-09-05 06:28:58.311793',0,'108190.jpg',1),(168,'GST on Resident Welfare Associations','Eversince the spurt of residential complexes and housing societies in India it was apparent that there was a need for someone to provide certain services for the common use of the residents of such complexes or societies. This is where Resident Welfare Associations (RWA) were born. RWA is an Association of Persons which provides certain services (usually maintenance services) to its own members.','','','2019-09-05 06:29:10.566666','2019-09-05 06:29:38.934724',0,'',1),(169,'Assessee directed to approach Nodal Officer w.r.t. less ITC credited in electronic credit leger on filing Tran-1','GST: Where assessee filed Form GST TRAN-1 on 28-9-2017 and received credit of Rs. 13.21 lakhs in its e-Credit Ledger; whereas it was entitled to credit of Rs. 83.20 lakhs and thereupon assessee re-filed Form GST TRAN-1 and received credit of only Rs. 5.17 lakhs in its e-Credit Ledger, assessee was directed to appear before Nodal Officer, who would pass a speaking order in this regard','','','2019-09-05 06:29:52.919193','2019-09-05 06:30:58.730384',0,'108240_qSbq4uk.jpg',1),(170,'\'Combined Refrigerator Freezer\' is classified under heading No. 8418 10 90','GST/EXCISE/ST/VAT: Where assessee imported \'combined refrigerator freezer\' and claimed same as \'refrigerator\' and declared classification on basis of code in certificate of origin under Heading No. 8418 21 00, rate of duty should be determined in accordance with Customs Tariff Act and a code in a certificate could not be sole basis for such determination and imported product was classifiable under Heading No. 8418 10 90','','','2019-09-05 06:31:10.556239','2019-09-05 06:31:57.017390',0,'108217.png',1);
